# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cleveland-ohio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland was founded in 1796 near the mouth of the Cuyahoga River as part of the Connecticut Western Reserve in modern-day Northeast Ohio by General Moses Cleaveland, after whom the city was named.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's location on the river and the lake shore allowed it to grow into a major commercial and industrial metropolis by the late 19th century, attracting large numbers of immigrants and migrants.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] It was among the top 10 largest U.S. cities by population for much of the 20th century, a period that saw the development of the city's cultural institutions.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy began to slow down as manufacturing declined and suburbanization occurred.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland is a port city, connected to the Atlantic Ocean via the St.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its economy relies on diverse sectors that include higher education, manufacturing, financial services, healthcare, and biomedicals.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city serves as the headquarters of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, as well as several major companies.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The GDP for Greater Cleveland was US$138.3 billion in 2022.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Combined with the Akron metropolitan area, the eight-county Cleveland–Akron metropolitan economy was $176 billion in 2022, the largest in Ohio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Known as "The Forest City" among many other nicknames, Cleveland serves as the center of the Cleveland Metroparks nature reserve system.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's major league professional sports teams include the Cleveland Browns (football; NFL), the Cleveland Cavaliers (basketball; NBA), and the Cleveland Guardians (baseball; MLB).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland was established on July 22, 1796, by surveyors of the Connecticut Land Company when they laid out Connecticut's Western Reserve into townships and a capital city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] They named the settlement "Cleaveland" after their leader, General Moses Cleaveland, a veteran of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleaveland oversaw the New England–style design of the plan for what would become the modern downtown area, centered on Public Square.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The town's name was often shortened to "Cleveland", including by Cleaveland's original surveyors.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A myth emerged that the spelling was altered by *The Cleveland Advertiser* to fit the name on the newspaper's masthead.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The first permanent European settler in Cleveland was Lorenzo Carter, who arrived in May 1797 and built a cabin on the banks of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The emerging community served as an important supply post for the U.S. during the Battle of Lake Erie in the War of 1812.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Largely through the efforts of the settlement's first lawyer, Alfred Kelley, the village of Cleveland was incorporated on December 23, 1814.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Despite the nearby swampy lowlands and harsh winters, the town's waterfront on Lake Erie was advantageous, giving it access to Great Lakes trade.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] It grew rapidly after the 1832 completion of the Ohio and Erie Canal, which linked the Ohio River and the Great Lakes to the Atlantic Ocean via the Erie Canal and Hudson River, and later via the Saint Lawrence Seaway.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The town's growth continued with added railroad links.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1836, Cleveland, then only on the eastern banks of the Cuyahoga, was incorporated as a city; John W.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The neighboring municipality of Ohio City was a major rival to Cleveland until its annexation by the city in 1854.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A center of abolitionist activity, Cleveland (code-named "Station Hope") was a major stop on the Underground Railroad for escaped African American slaves en route to Canada.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city served as an important center for the Union during the American Civil War, creating a large manufacturing industry within the city and unprecedented growth.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its geographic location as a transportation hub on the Great Lakes contributed to its development as an industrial and commercial center.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Rockefeller founded Standard Oil in Cleveland; in 1885, he moved its headquarters to New York City.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's economic growth and industrial jobs attracted large waves of immigrants from Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, and Ireland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Urban growth was accompanied by labor unrest as workers demanded better wages and working conditions.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Streetcar Strike of 1899 was one of the more violent instances of labor strife in the city during this period.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] By 1910, Cleveland had become known as the "Sixth City" due to its status at the time as the sixth-largest U.S. city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its automotive companies included Peerless, Chandler, and Winton, maker of the first car driven across the U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Other manufacturing industries in Cleveland included steam cars produced by White and electric cars produced by Baker.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Euclid Avenue became known as "Millionaires' Row" for its prestige and elegance.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Major Progressive Era politicians were leaders in the city, including populist Mayor Tom L.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Johnson, who was responsible for the development of the Cleveland Mall Plan.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The era of the City Beautiful movement in Cleveland architecture saw wealthy patrons support the establishment of the city's major cultural institutions including the Cleveland Museum of Art, which opened in 1916, and the Cleveland Orchestra, established in 1918.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] African American migrants from the rural South arrived in Cleveland as part of the Great Migration for jobs, constitutional rights, and relief from racial discrimination.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] By 1920 Cleveland had grown into a densely populated metropolis of 796,841, making it the fifth-largest city in the nation, with a foreign-born population of 30%.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Radical labor movements gained popularity in the city, such as the Industrial Workers of the World (IWW), in response to the conditions of the largely immigrant and migrant workers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1919, local socialist and IWW demonstrators clashed with anti-socialists in the May Day Riots, which occurred amid the First Red Scare and the strike wave that swept the U.S. that year.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's population grew throughout the Roaring Twenties.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The decade saw the establishment of the city's Playhouse Square, and the rise of the risqué Short Vincent.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Bal-Masque balls of the avant-garde Kokoon Arts Club scandalized the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Jazz came to prominence in Cleveland during this period.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Prohibition was established in Ohio in May 1919 (although it was not well-enforced in Cleveland), became law with the Volstead Act in 1920, and was repealed nationally by Congress in 1933.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The ban on alcohol led to the rise of speakeasies throughout the city and organized crime gangs, such as the Mayfield Road Mob, who smuggled bootleg liquor across Lake Erie from Canada into Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1929, Cleveland hosted the first of many National Air Races, and Amelia Earhart flew to the city from Santa Monica, California in the Women's Air Derby.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Van Sweringen brothers commenced construction of the Terminal Tower skyscraper in 1926 and oversaw its completion in 1927.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] When the building was dedicated as part of Cleveland Union Terminal in 1930, the city had a population of over 900,000.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's economy was greatly effected by the Wall Street Crash of 1929 and Great Depression.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A center of union activity, the city saw significant labor struggles in this period, including strikes by workers against Fisher Body in 1936 and against Republic Steel in 1937.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city was aided by major federal works projects sponsored by President Franklin D.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In commemoration of the centennial of Cleveland's incorporation as a city, the Great Lakes Exposition debuted in June 1936 at the city's North Coast Harbor, along the Lake Erie shore north of downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Conceived by Cleveland's business leaders as a way to revitalize the city during the Depression, it drew four million visitors in its first season, and seven million by the end of its second and final season in September 1937.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] During World War II, Cleveland was a major hub of the U.S. war effort as the fifth largest manufacturing center in the nation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] During the war the city established the Cleveland Transit System, the predecessor to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland experienced an economic boom after the war and businesses declared the city to be the "best location in the nation".
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The decade saw the rising popularity of the rock and roll music genre.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] By the 1960s, Cleveland's economy slowed and residents sought new housing in the suburbs, reflecting national trends of suburban growth following federally subsidized highways.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Industrial restructuring, particularly in the steel and automotive industries, resulted in the loss of numerous jobs in Cleveland and the city suffered economically.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The burning of the Cuyahoga River in June 1969 brought national attention to the issue of industrial pollution in Cleveland and catalyzed the American environmental movement.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Housing discrimination and redlining against African Americans led to racial unrest in Cleveland; the Hough riots erupted from July 18 to 24, 1966, and the Glenville Shootout took place on July 23, 1968.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In November 1967, Cleveland became the first major American city to elect an African American mayor, Carl B.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Stokes, who worked to restore the Cuyahoga River.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] During the 1970s, Cleveland was known as "Bomb City U.S.A." due to several bombings that shook the city, mostly due to organized crime rivalries.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In December 1978, Cleveland became the first major American city since the Great Depression to enter a financial default on federal loans.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The national recession of the early 1980s eroded the city's traditional economic industries; Cleveland's unemployment rate of 13.8% was higher than the national average due to the closure of several steel production centers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city began an economic recovery in the 1980s.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Although the city emerged from default in 1987, it suffered from the impact of the subprime mortgage crisis and the Great Recession.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] By the 21st century, Cleveland had developed a more diversified economy and gained a national reputation as a center for healthcare and the arts.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's downtown and several neighborhoods experienced significant population growth since 2010, while overall population decline has slowed.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city has a total area of 82.47 square miles (213.6 km2), of which 77.70 square miles (201.2 km2) is land and 4.77 square miles (12.4 km2) is water.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The shore of Lake Erie is 569 feet (173 m) above sea level; the city lies on a series of irregular bluffs lying roughly parallel to the lake.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In Cleveland, these bluffs are cut principally by the Cuyahoga River, Big Creek, and Euclid Creek.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The land rises quickly from the lake shore elevation of 569 feet.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Public Square, less than one mile (1.6 km) inland, sits at an elevation of 650 feet (198 m), and Hopkins Airport, five miles (8.0 km) inland from the lake, is at an elevation of 791 feet (241 m).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland borders several inner-ring and streetcar suburbs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the west, it borders Lakewood, Rocky River, and Fairview Park, and to the east, it borders Shaker Heights, Cleveland Heights, South Euclid, and East Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the southwest, it borders Linndale, Brooklyn, Parma, and Brook Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the south, the city borders Newburgh Heights, Cuyahoga Heights, and Brooklyn Heights and to the southeast, it borders Warrensville Heights, Maple Heights, and Garfield Heights.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] To the northeast, along the shore of Lake Erie, Cleveland borders Bratenahl and Euclid.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Many of the city's government and civic buildings, including City Hall, the Cuyahoga County Courthouse, the Cleveland Public Library, and Public Auditorium, are clustered around the open Cleveland Mall and share a common neoclassical architecture.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] They were built in the early 20th century as the result of the 1903 Group Plan.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] They constitute one of the most complete examples of City Beautiful design.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Completed in 1927 and dedicated in 1930 as part of the Cleveland Union Terminal complex, the Terminal Tower is a prototypical Beaux-Arts skyscraper.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] It was the tallest building in North America outside New York City until 1964 and the tallest in the city until 1991.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Key Tower (the tallest building in Ohio) and 200 Public Square combine elements of Art Deco architecture with postmodern designs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Nicknamed Cleveland's "Crystal Palace", the five-story Cleveland Arcade (also known as the Old Arcade) was built in 1890 and renovated in 2001 as a Hyatt Regency Hotel.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Trust Company Building was completed in 1907 and renovated in 2015 as a downtown Heinen's supermarket.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's historic ecclesiastical architecture includes the Presbyterian Old Stone Church, the onion-domed St.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Theodosius Russian Orthodox Cathedral, and the Roman Catholic Cathedral of St.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] John the Evangelist along with several other ethnically inspired Catholic churches.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland City Planning Commission has designated 34 neighborhoods in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Centered on Public Square, Downtown Cleveland is the city's central business district, encompassing subdistricts such as the Nine-Twelve District, the Campus District, the Civic Center, East 4th Street, Playhouse Square, and the Short Vincent entertainment district.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Mixed-use areas, such as the Warehouse District and the Superior Arts District, are occupied by industrial and office buildings as well as restaurants, cafes, and bars.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The number of condominiums, lofts, and apartments has been on the increase since 2000 and especially 2010, reflecting downtown's growing population.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clevelanders geographically define themselves by whether they live on the east or west side of the Cuyahoga River.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The East Side includes the neighborhoods of Buckeye–Shaker, Buckeye–Woodhill, Central, Collinwood (including Nottingham), Euclid–Green, Fairfax, Glenville, Goodrich–Kirtland Park (including Asiatown), Hough, Kinsman, Lee–Miles (including Lee–Harvard and Lee–Seville), Mount Pleasant, St.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clair–Superior, Union–Miles Park, and University Circle (including Little Italy).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cuyahoga Valley neighborhood (including Whiskey Island and the Flats) is situated between the East and West Sides, while Broadway–Slavic Village is sometimes referred to as the South Side.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Several neighborhoods have seen the return of the middle class that left the city for the suburbs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] These include Ohio City, Tremont, Detroit–Shoreway, and Edgewater on the West Side, and Collinwood, Hough, Fairfax, and Little Italy on the East Side.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The growth was spurred by attracting creative class members, which has facilitated new residential development and the transformation of old industrial buildings into loft spaces for artists.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland exhibits a humid continental (Köppen: *Dfa*) or humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) climate, depending on the isotherm used.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Due to its proximity to Lake Erie, Cleveland experiences milder temperatures than much of Ohio, with relatively cooler summers and warmer winters.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] East of the mouth of the Cuyahoga, the land elevation rises rapidly in the south.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Together with the prevailing winds off Lake Erie, this feature is the principal contributor to the lake-effect snow that is typical in Cleveland (especially on the city's East Side) from mid-November until the surface of the lake freezes, usually in late January or early February.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The lake effect causes a relative differential in geographical snowfall totals across the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] On the city's far West Side, the Hopkins neighborhood only reached 100 inches (254 cm) of snowfall in a season three times since record-keeping for snow began in 1893.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] By contrast, seasonal totals approaching or exceeding 100 inches (254 cm) are not uncommon as the city ascends into the Heights on the east, where the region known as the "Snow Belt" begins.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Extending from the city's East Side and its suburbs, the Snow Belt reaches up the Lake Erie shore as far as Buffalo.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The all-time record high in Cleveland of 104 °F (40 °C) was established on June 25, 1988, and the all-time record low of −20 °F (−29 °C) was set on January 19, 1994.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] On average, July is the warmest month with a mean temperature of 74.5 °F (23.6 °C), and January, with a mean temperature of 29.1 °F (−1.6 °C), is the coldest.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Normal yearly precipitation based on the 30-year average from 1991 to 2020 is 41.03 inches (1,042 mm).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The least precipitation occurs on the western side and directly along the lake, and the most occurs in the eastern suburbs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Parts of Geauga County to the east receive over 44 inches (1,100 mm) of liquid precipitation annually.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] With its extensive cleanup of its Lake Erie shore and the Cuyahoga River, Cleveland has been recognized by national media as an environmental success story and a national leader in environmental protection.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Since the city's industrialization, the Cuyahoga River had become so affected by industrial pollution that it "caught fire" a total of 13 times beginning in 1868.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] It was the river fire of June 1969 that spurred the city to action under Mayor Carl B.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Stokes, and played a key role in the passage of the Clean Water Act in 1972 and the National Environmental Policy Act later that year.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Since that time, the Cuyahoga has been extensively cleaned up through the efforts of the city and the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency (OEPA).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition to continued efforts to improve freshwater and air quality, Cleveland is now exploring renewable energy.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's two main electrical utilities are FirstEnergy and Cleveland Public Power.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its climate action plan, updated in December 2018, has a 2050 target of 100% renewable power, along with reduction of greenhouse gases to 80% below the 2010 level.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In recent decades, Cleveland has been working to address the issue of harmful algal blooms on Lake Erie, fed primarily by agricultural runoff, which have presented new environmental challenges for the city and for northern Ohio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has seen a population decline over the past century.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's population was 914,808 according to the 1950 Census.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] According to the 2020 census, there were 372,624 people and 170,549 households in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The population density was 4,901.51 inhabitants per square mile (1,892.5/km2).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The median household income was $30,907 and the per capita income was $21,223.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] 32.7% of the population was living below the poverty line.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Of the city's population over the age of 25, 17.5% held a bachelor's degree or higher, and 80.8% had a high school diploma or equivalent.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] As of 2020, the racial and ethnic composition of the city was 47.5% African American, 32.1% non-Hispanic white, 13.1% Hispanic or Latino, 2.8% Asian, 0.2% Native American, and 3.8% from two or more races.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] 85.3% of Clevelanders age five and older spoke only English at home, while 14.7% spoke a language other than English, including Spanish, Arabic, Chinese, Hungarian, Albanian, and various Slavic languages (Russian, Polish, Serbian, Croatian, and Slovene).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's spoken accent is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English, similar to other Great Lakes cities, but distinctive from the rest of Ohio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] , now serves an African American congregation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, Cleveland saw a massive influx of immigrants from Ireland, Italy, and the Austro-Hungarian, German, Russian, and Ottoman empires, most of whom were attracted by manufacturing jobs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The presence of Hungarians within Cleveland proper was, at one time, so great that the city boasted the highest concentration of Hungarians in the world outside of Budapest.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has a long-established Jewish community, historically centered on the East Side neighborhoods of Glenville and Kinsman, but now mostly concentrated in East Side suburbs such as Cleveland Heights and Beachwood, location of the Maltz Museum of Jewish Heritage.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the South.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Between 1910 and 1970, the black population of Cleveland, largely concentrated on the city's East Side, increased significantly as a result of the First and Second Great Migrations.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's Latino community consists primarily of Puerto Ricans, as well as smaller numbers of immigrants from Mexico, Cuba, the Dominican Republic, South and Central America, and Spain.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's Asian community, centered on historical Asiatown, consists of Chinese, Koreans, Vietnamese, and other groups.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Additionally, the city and the county have significant communities of Albanians, Arabs (especially Lebanese, Syrians, and Palestinians), Armenians, French, Greeks, Iranians, Scots, Turks, and West Indians.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A 2020 analysis found Cleveland to be the most ethnically and racially diverse major city in Ohio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The influx of immigrants in the 19th and early 20th centuries drastically transformed Cleveland's religious landscape.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] From a homogeneous settlement of New England Protestants, it evolved into a city with a diverse religious composition.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The predominant faith among Clevelanders today is Christianity, with Jewish, Muslim, Hindu, and Buddhist minorities.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Within Cleveland, the neighborhoods with the highest foreign-born populations are Asiatown/Goodrich–Kirtland Park (32.7%), Clark–Fulton (26.7%), West Boulevard (18.5%), Brooklyn Centre (17.3%), Downtown (17.2%), University Circle (15.9%, with 20% in Little Italy), and Jefferson (14.3%).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Recent waves of immigration have brought new groups to Cleveland, including Ethiopians and South Asians, as well as immigrants from Russia and the former USSR, Southeast Europe (especially Albania), the Middle East, East Asia, and Latin America.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In the 2010s, the immigrant population of Cleveland and Cuyahoga County began to see significant growth.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A 2019 study found Cleveland to be the city with the shortest average processing time in the nation for immigrants to become U.S. citizens.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's annual One World Day in Rockefeller Park includes a naturalization ceremony of new immigrants.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's location on the Cuyahoga River and Lake Erie has been key to its growth as a major commercial center.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Steel and many other manufactured goods emerged as leading industries.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city has since diversified its economy in addition to its manufacturing sector.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Established in 1914, the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland is one of 12 U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its downtown building, located on East 6th Street and Superior Avenue, was completed in 1923 by the Cleveland architectural firm Walker and Weeks.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The headquarters of the Federal Reserve System's Fourth District, the bank employs 1,000 people and maintains branch offices in Cincinnati and Pittsburgh.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland and Cuyahoga County are home to *Fortune 500* companies Cleveland-Cliffs, Progressive, Sherwin-Williams, Parker-Hannifin, KeyCorp, and Travel Centers of America.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] NASA maintains the Glenn Research Center in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Jones Day, one of the largest law firms in the U.S., was founded in Cleveland in 1893.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Healthcare plays a major role in Cleveland's economy.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's "Big Three" hospital systems are the Cleveland Clinic, University Hospitals, and MetroHealth.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Clinic is the largest private employer in the state of Ohio, with a workforce of over 55,000 as of 2022.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] It carries the distinction of being one of the best hospital systems in the world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The clinic is led by Croatian-born president and CEO Tomislav Mihaljevic and it is affiliated with Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] University Hospitals includes the University Hospitals Cleveland Medical Center and its Rainbow Babies & Children's Hospital.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cliff Megerian serves as that system's CEO.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] MetroHealth on the city's west side is led by president and CEO Christine Alexander-Rager.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Formerly known as City Hospital, it operates one of two Level I trauma centers in the city, and has various locations throughout Greater Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 2013, Cleveland's Global Center for Health Innovation opened with 235,000 square feet (21,800 m2) of display space for healthcare companies across the world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] To take advantage of the proximity of universities and other medical centers in Cleveland, the Veterans Administration moved the region's VA hospital from suburban Brecksville to a new facility in University Circle.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's Playhouse Square is the second largest performing arts center in the U.S. behind New York City's Lincoln Center.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] It includes the State, Palace, Allen, Hanna, and Ohio theaters.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The theaters host Broadway musicals, special concerts, speaking engagements, and other events throughout the year.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Playhouse Square's resident performing arts companies include Cleveland Ballet, the Cleveland International Film Festival, the Cleveland Play House, Cleveland State University Department of Theatre and Dance, DANCECleveland, the Great Lakes Theater Festival, and the Tri-C Jazz Fest.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A city with strong traditions in theater and vaudeville, Cleveland has produced many renowned performers, most prominently comedian Bob Hope.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Outside Playhouse Square is Karamu House, the oldest African American theater in the nation, established in 1915.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] On the West Side, the Gordon Square Arts District in the Detroit–Shoreway neighborhood is the location of the Capitol Theatre, the Near West Theatre, and an Off-Off-Broadway playhouse, the Cleveland Public Theatre.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Dobama Theatre and the Beck Center for the Arts are based in Cleveland's streetcar suburbs of Cleveland Heights and Lakewood respectively.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Orchestra is widely considered one of the world's finest orchestras, and often referred to as the finest in the nation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] It is one of the "Big Five" major orchestras in the U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The orchestra plays at Severance Hall in University Circle during the winter and at Blossom Music Center in Cuyahoga Falls during the summer.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] One Playhouse Square, now the headquarters for Cleveland's public broadcasters, was initially used as the broadcast studios of WJW (AM), where disc jockey Alan Freed first popularized the term "rock and roll".
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Beginning in the 1950s, Cleveland gained a strong reputation as a key breakout market for rock music.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Its popularity in the city was so great that Billy Bass, the program director at the WMMS radio station, referred to Cleveland as "The Rock and Roll Capital of the World".
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Agora Theatre and Ballroom has served as a major venue for rock concerts in the city since the 1960s.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] From 1974 through 1980, the city hosted the World Series of Rock at Cleveland Municipal Stadium.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Jazz and R&B have a long history in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Many major figures in jazz performed in the city, including Louis Armstrong, Cab Calloway, Duke Ellington, Ella Fitzgerald, Dizzy Gillespie, and Billie Holiday.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Legendary pianist Art Tatum regularly played in Cleveland clubs in the 1930s, and gypsy jazz guitarist Django Reinhardt gave his U.S. debut performance in Cleveland in 1946.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Prominent jazz artist Noble Sissle was a graduate of Cleveland Central High School, and Artie Shaw worked and performed in Cleveland early in his career.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Tri-C Jazz Fest has been held annually in Cleveland at Playhouse Square since 1980, and the Cleveland Jazz Orchestra was established in 1984.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city has a history of polka music being popular both past and present and is the location of the Polka Hall of Fame.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A subgenre called Cleveland-style polka, named after the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The music's popularity is due in part to the success of Frankie Yankovic, a Cleveland native who was considered "America's Polka King".
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The first film shot in Cleveland was in 1897 by the company of Ohioan Thomas Edison.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Before Hollywood became the center for American cinema, filmmaker Samuel Brodsky and playwright Robert McLaughlin operated a film studio at the Andrews mansion on Euclid Avenue (now the WEWS-TV studio).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] There they produced major silent-era features, such as *Dangerous Toys* (1921), which are now considered lost.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Brodsky also directed the weekly *Plain Dealer Screen Magazine* that ran in theaters in Cleveland and Ohio from 1917 to 1924.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition, Cleveland hosted over a dozen sponsored film studios, including Cinécraft Productions, which still operates in Ohio City.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In the "talkie" era, Cleveland featured in several major studio films, such as Michael Curtiz's pre-Code classic *Goodbye Again* (1933) with Warren William and Joan Blondell.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Players from the 1948 Cleveland Indians appeared in *The Kid from Cleveland* (1949).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Billy Wilder's *The Fortune Cookie* (1966) was set and filmed in the city and marked the first onscreen pairing of Walter Matthau and Jack Lemmon.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Labor struggles in Cleveland were depicted in *Native Land* (1942), narrated by Paul Robeson, and in Norman Jewison's *F.I.S.T.* (1978) with Sylvester Stallone.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clevelander Jim Jarmusch's *Stranger Than Paradise* (1984) – a deadpan comedy about two New Yorkers who travel to Florida by way of Cleveland – was a favorite of the Cannes Film Festival.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Major League* (1989) reflected the perennial struggles of the Cleveland Indians, while *American Splendor* (2003) reflected the life of Cleveland graphic novelist Harvey Pekar.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Kill the Irishman* (2011) depicted the 1970s turf war between Danny Greene and the Cleveland crime family.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has doubled for other locations in films.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The wedding and reception scenes in *The Deer Hunter* (1978), while set in suburban Pittsburgh, were shot in Cleveland's Tremont neighborhood.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] *A Christmas Story* (1983) was set in Indiana, but drew many external shots from Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The opening shots of *Air Force One* (1997) were filmed in and above Severance Hall, and *Judas and the Black Messiah* (2021) was filmed in Cleveland, although set in Chicago.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Downtown Cleveland doubled for Manhattan in *Spider-Man 3* (2007), *The Avengers* (2012), and *The Fate of the Furious* (2017), and for Metropolis in James Gunn's *Superman* (2025).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Future productions are handled by the Greater Cleveland Film Commission at the Leader Building on Superior Avenue.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In television, the city is the setting for the popular network sitcom *The Drew Carey Show*, starring Cleveland native Drew Carey.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Hot in Cleveland*, a comedy that aired on TV Land, premiered on June 16, 2010, and ran for six seasons until its finale on June 3, 2015.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] *Cleveland Hustles*, the CNBC reality show co-created by LeBron James, was filmed in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has a thriving literary and poetry community, with regular poetry readings at bookstores, coffee shops, and various other venues.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 1925, Russian Futurist poet Vladimir Mayakovsky came to Cleveland and gave a poetry recitation to the city's ethnic working class, as part of his trip to America.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland State University Poetry Center serves as an academic center for poetry in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Langston Hughes, preeminent poet of the Harlem Renaissance and child of an itinerant couple, lived in Cleveland as a teenager and attended Central High School in Cleveland in the 1910s.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] At Central High, the young writer was taught by Helen Maria Chesnutt, daughter of Cleveland-born African American novelist Charles W.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Hughes authored some of his earliest poems, plays, and short stories in Cleveland and contributed to the school newspaper.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The African American avant-garde poet Russell Atkins lived in the city as well.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The American modernist poet Hart Crane was born in nearby Garrettsville, Ohio in 1899.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] His adolescence was divided between Cleveland and Akron before he moved to New York City in 1916.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland was the home of Joe Shuster and Jerry Siegel, who created the comic book character Superman in 1933.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Harlan Ellison, noted author of speculative fiction, was born in Cleveland in 1934.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] As a young man, he published a series of short stories appearing in the *Cleveland News*, and performed in a number of productions for the Cleveland Play House.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland is the site of the Anisfield-Wolf Book Award, which recognizes books that have contributed to the understanding of racism and human diversity.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Presented by the Cleveland Foundation, it remains the only American book prize focusing on works that address racism and diversity.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Museum of Art is a major American art museum, with a collection that includes more than 60,000 works of art.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Museum of Contemporary Art Cleveland showcases established and emerging artists, particularly from the Cleveland area, through hosting and producing temporary exhibitions.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Both museums offer free admission to visitors.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The two museums are part of Cleveland's University Circle, a 550-acre (2.2 km2) concentration of cultural, educational, and medical institutions located 5 miles (8.0 km) east of downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition to the art museums, the neighborhood includes the Cleveland Botanical Garden, Case Western Reserve University, University Hospitals, Severance Hall, the Maltz Performing Arts Center, the Cleveland Museum of Natural History, and the Western Reserve Historical Society.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Also located at University Circle is the Cleveland Cinematheque at the Cleveland Institute of Art.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Pei-designed Rock and Roll Hall of Fame is located on Cleveland's Lake Erie waterfront at North Coast Harbor downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Neighboring attractions include Cleveland Browns Stadium, the Great Lakes Science Center, the Steamship Mather Museum, the International Women's Air & Space Museum, and the USS *Cod*, a World War II submarine.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Scofield, the Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument at Public Square is Cleveland's major Civil War memorial and a major attraction in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Other city attractions include Grays Armory, the Cleveland Masonic Temple, and the Children's Museum of Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] A Cleveland holiday attraction, especially for fans of Jean Shepherd's *A Christmas Story*, is the Christmas Story House and Museum in Tremont.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland hosts the WinterLand holiday display lighting festival annually at Public Square.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland International Film Festival has been held in the city since 1977, and the Cleveland Silent Film Festival has been held since 2022.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland National Air Show, an indirect successor to the National Air Races, has been held at the city's Burke Lakefront Airport since 1964.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Great Lakes Burning River Fest, a two-night music and beer festival at Whiskey Island, has been sponsored by the Great Lakes Brewing Company since 2001.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Many ethnic festivals are held in Cleveland throughout the year.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] These include the annual Feast of the Assumption in Little Italy, Russian Maslenitsa in Rockefeller Park, the Puerto Rican Parade and Cultural Festival in Clark–Fulton, the Cleveland Asian Festival in Asiatown, the Tremont Greek Fest, and the St.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland also hosts annual Polish Dyngus Day and Slovene Kurentovanje celebrations.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The city's annual Saint Patrick's Day parade brings hundreds of thousands to the streets of Downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] The Cleveland Thyagaraja Festival held each spring at Cleveland State University is the largest Indian classical music and dance festival in the world outside of India.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Since 1946, the city has annually marked One World Day in the Cleveland Cultural Gardens in Rockefeller Park, celebrating all of its ethnic communities.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland's mosaic of ethnic communities and their various culinary traditions have long played an important role in defining the city's cuisine.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Local mainstays include an abundance of Slavic, Hungarian, and Central-Eastern European contributions, such as kielbasa, stuffed cabbage, pierogies, goulash, and chicken paprikash.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Italian, German, Irish, and Jewish cuisines are also prominent in Cleveland, as are Lebanese, Greek, Chinese, Puerto Rican, Mexican, and numerous other ethnic cuisines.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Vendors at the West Side Market in Ohio City offer many ethnic foods for sale.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In addition, the city boasts a vibrant barbecue and soul food scene.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Slyman's Deli on Cleveland's near East Side is notable for its corned beef sandwich, with patrons including former U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Another celebrated sandwich, the Polish Boy, is a popular street food and Cleveland original frequently sold at downtown hot dog carts and stadium concession stands.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Brown stadium mustard is synonymous with Cleveland, especially Bertman Original Ballpark Mustard.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Another notable local food item with Depression-era roots is city chicken.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] With its blue-collar roots well intact, and plenty of Lake Erie perch and walleye available, the tradition of Friday night fish fries remains alive and thriving in Cleveland, particularly in ethnic parish-based settings, especially during the season of Lent.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Clambakes are likewise embedded into the city's culinary culture.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] For dessert, the Cleveland Cassata Cake is a unique treat invented in the local Italian community and served in Italian establishments throughout the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Another popular dessert, the locally crafted Russian Tea Biscuit, is common in many Jewish bakeries in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland is noted in the world of celebrity food culture.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Famous local figures include chef Michael Symon and food writer Michael Ruhlman, both of whom achieved local and national attention for their contributions to the culinary world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] In 2007, Symon helped gain the spotlight when he was named "The Next Iron Chef" on the Food Network.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] That same year, Ruhlman collaborated with Anthony Bourdain, to do an episode of his *Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations* focusing on Cleveland's restaurant scene.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Ohio produces the fifth most beer in the U.S., with its largest brewery being Cleveland's Great Lakes Brewing Company.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland has had a long history of brewing, tied to many of its ethnic immigrants, and has reemerged as a regional leader in production.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Dozens of breweries exist within city limits, including large producers such as Market Garden Brewery.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Although breweries can be found throughout the city, the highest concentration is in the Ohio City neighborhood.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p01] Cleveland hosts expansions from other countries as well, including the Scottish BrewDog and German Hofbrauhaus.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's major professional sports teams are the Cleveland Guardians (Major League Baseball), the Cleveland Browns (National Football League), and the Cleveland Cavaliers (National Basketball Association).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Other professional teams include the Cleveland Monsters (American Hockey League), the Cleveland Charge (NBA G League), the Cleveland Crunch (Major League Indoor Soccer), Cleveland SC (National Premier Soccer League), and the Cleveland Fusion (Women's Football Alliance).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Local sporting venues include Progressive Field, Huntington Bank Field, Rocket Arena, the Wolstein Center, and Public Auditorium.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Guardians – known as the Indians from 1915 to 2021 – won the World Series in 1920 and 1948.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] They also won the American League pennant, making the World Series in the 1954, 1995, 1997, and 2016 seasons.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Between 1995 and 2001, the team sold out 455 consecutive games, a Major League Baseball record that stood until 2008.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Historically, the Browns have been among the most successful franchises in American football history, winning eight titles during a short period of time – 1946, 1947, 1948, 1949, 1950, 1954, 1955, and 1964.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Browns have never played in a Super Bowl, getting close five times by making it to the NFL/AFC Championship Game in 1968, 1969, 1986, 1987, and 1989.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Former owner Art Modell's relocation of the Browns after the 1995 season caused tremendous heartbreak and resentment among local fans.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] After a series of lawsuits, a compromise was reached between Modell, Cleveland mayor Michael R.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] White, and NFL and Commissioner Paul Tagliabue to bring back the Browns beginning in the 1999 season, retaining all team history.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In Cleveland's earlier football history, the Cleveland Bulldogs won the NFL Championship in 1924, and the Cleveland Rams won the NFL Championship in 1945 before relocating to Los Angeles.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cavaliers won the Eastern Conference in 2007, 2015, 2016, 2017 and 2018 but were defeated in the NBA Finals by the San Antonio Spurs and then by the Golden State Warriors, respectively.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cavs won the Conference again in 2016 and won their first NBA Championship coming back from a 3–1 deficit, finally defeating the Golden State Warriors.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Afterwards, over 1.3 million people attended a parade held in the Cavs' honor on June 22, 2016, in downtown Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Previously, the Cleveland Rosenblums dominated the original American Basketball League, and the Cleveland Pipers, owned by George Steinbrenner, won the American Basketball League championship in 1962.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Monsters of the American Hockey League won the 2016 Calder Cup.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] They were the first Cleveland AHL team to do so since the 1964 Barons.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Collegiately, NCAA Division I Cleveland State Vikings have 19 varsity sports, nationally known for their Cleveland State Vikings men's basketball team.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] NCAA Division III Case Western Reserve Spartans have 17 varsity sports, most known for their Case Western Reserve Spartans football team.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The headquarters of the Mid-American Conference (MAC) are in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The conference stages both its men's and women's basketball tournaments at Rocket Arena.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Marathon has been hosted annually since 1978, and a monument commemorating one of Cleveland's most prominent track and field athletes, Jesse Owens, stands at the city's Fort Huntington Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The second American Chess Congress, a predecessor to the U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Championship, was held in Cleveland in 1871, and won by George Henry Mackenzie.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Open Chess Championships took place in the city, and were won by Edward Lasker and Bobby Fischer, respectively.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2014, Cleveland hosted the ninth official Gay Games ceremony.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In July 2024, the city hosted the Pan American Masters Games.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Known locally as the "Emerald Necklace", the Olmsted-inspired Cleveland Metroparks encircle Cleveland and Cuyahoga County.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The city proper encompasses the Metroparks' Brookside and Lakefront Reservations, as well as significant parts of the Rocky River, Washington, and Euclid Creek Reservations.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Lakefront Reservation, which provides public access to Lake Erie, consists of four parks: Edgewater Park, Whiskey Island–Wendy Park, East 55th Street Marina, and Gordon Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Three more parks fall under the jurisdiction of the Euclid Creek Reservation: Euclid Beach, Villa Angela, and Wildwood Marina.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Further south, bike and hiking trails in the Brecksville and Bedford Reservations, along with Garfield Park, provide access to trails in the Cuyahoga Valley National Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Also included in the Metroparks system is the Cleveland Metroparks Zoo, established in 1882.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Located in Big Creek Valley, the zoo has one of the largest collections of primates in North America.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition to the Metroparks, the Cleveland Public Parks District oversees the city's neighborhood parks, the largest of which is the historic Rockefeller Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The latter is notable for its late 19th century landmark bridges, the Rockefeller Park Greenhouse, and the Cleveland Cultural Gardens, which celebrate the city's ethnic diversity.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Just outside of Rockefeller Park, the Cleveland Botanical Garden in University Circle, established in 1930, is the oldest civic garden center in the nation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition, the Greater Cleveland Aquarium, located in the historic FirstEnergy Powerhouse in the Flats, is the only independent, free-standing aquarium in the state of Ohio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland operates on a mayor–council (strong mayor) form of government, in which the mayor is the chief executive and the city council serves as the legislative branch.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] City council members are elected from 15 wards to four-year terms.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] From 1924 to 1931, the city briefly experimented with a council–manager government under William R.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Morgan before returning to the mayor–council system.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by Cleveland Municipal Court, the first municipal court in the state.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] District Court for the Northern District of Ohio, based at the Carl B.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Chief Judge for the Northern District is Sara Elizabeth Lioi and the Clerk of Court is Sandy Opacich.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The office of the mayor has been held by Justin Bibb since 2022.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Previous mayors include progressive Democrat Tom L.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Johnson, World War I-era War Secretary and BakerHostetler founder Newton D.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Supreme Court Justice Harold Hitz Burton, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator Frank J.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Health, Education, and Welfare Secretary Anthony J.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Celebrezze, two-term Ohio Governor and Senator George Voinovich, former U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Congressman Dennis Kucinich, and Carl B.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Stokes, the first African American mayor of a major U.S. city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Jackson was the city's longest-serving mayor.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The President of Cleveland City Council is Blaine Griffin, the council Majority Leader is Jasmin Santana, and the Majority Whip is Charles Slife.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Patricia Britt serves as the Clerk of Council.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Historically, from the Civil War era to the 1940s, Cleveland had been dominated by the Republican Party, with the notable exceptions of the Johnson and Baker mayoral administrations.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Businessman and Senator Mark Hanna was among Cleveland's most influential Republican figures, both locally and nationally.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Another nationally prominent Ohio Republican, former U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Garfield, was born in Cuyahoga County's Orange Township (today the Cleveland suburb of Moreland Hills).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Garfield Memorial in Cleveland's Lake View Cemetery.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Today Cleveland is a major stronghold for the Democratic Party in Ohio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Although local elections are nonpartisan, Democrats still dominate every level of government.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Politically, Cleveland and several of its neighboring suburbs comprise Ohio's 11th congressional district.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The district is represented by Shontel Brown, one of five Democrats representing the state of Ohio in the U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland has hosted three Republican national conventions, in 1924, 1936, and 2016.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Additionally, the city hosted the 1864 Radical Democratic National Convention.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Although Cleveland has not hosted a national convention for the Democrats, it has hosted several national election debates, including the second 1980 U.S. presidential debate, the 2004 U.S. vice presidential debate, one 2008 Democratic primary debate, and the first 2020 U.S. presidential debate.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Founded in 1912, the City Club of Cleveland provides a platform for national and local debates and discussions.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Known as Cleveland's "Citadel of Free Speech", it is one of the oldest continuous independent free speech and debate forums in the country.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The current Safety Director for the city of Cleveland is Dornat "Wayne" Drummond.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Like in other major American cities, crime in Cleveland is concentrated in areas with higher rates of poverty and lower access to jobs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In recent decades, the rate of crime in the city, although higher than the national average, experienced a significant decline, following a nationwide trend in falling crime rates.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] However, as in other major U.S. cities, crime in Cleveland saw an abrupt rise in 2020–21.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's law enforcement agency is the Cleveland Division of Police, established in 1866.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The division had roughly 1,100 sworn officers as of 2024, covering five police districts.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The district system was introduced in the 1930s by Cleveland Public Safety Director Eliot Ness (of the Untouchables), who later ran for mayor of Cleveland in 1947.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition, the Cuyahoga County Sheriff's Office is based in Downtown Cleveland at the Justice Center Complex.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by the firefighters of the Cleveland Division of Fire, established in 1863.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The fire department operates out of 22 active fire stations throughout the city in five battalions.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Each Battalion is commanded by a Battalion Chief, who reports to an on-duty Assistant Chief.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Division of Fire operates a fire apparatus fleet of twenty-two engine companies, eight ladder companies, three tower companies, two task force rescue squad companies, hazardous materials ("haz-mat") unit, and numerous other special, support, and reserve units.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The interim Chief of Department is Wayne Naida.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland EMS is operated by the city as its own municipal third-service EMS division.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland EMS is the primary provider of Advanced Life Support and ambulance transport within the city of Cleveland, while Cleveland Fire assists by providing fire response medical care.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Although a merger between the fire and EMS departments was proposed in the past, the idea was subsequently abandoned.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The EMS Commissioner is Orlando Wheeler.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland serves as headquarters to Coast Guard District 9 and is responsible for all U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Coast Guard operations on the five Great Lakes, the Saint Lawrence Seaway, and surrounding states accumulating 6,700 miles of shoreline and 1,500 miles of international shoreline with Canada.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Station Cleveland Harbor, located in North Coast Harbor, has a responsibility covering about 550 square miles of the federally navigable waters of Lake Erie, including the Cuyahoga and Rocky rivers, as well as a number of their tributaries.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by the Cleveland Metropolitan School District.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] It is the only K–12 district in Ohio under the direct control of the mayor, who appoints a school board.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Approximately 1 square mile (2.6 km2) of Cleveland's Buckeye–Shaker neighborhood is part of the Shaker Heights City School District.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The area, which has been a part of the Shaker school district since the 1920s, permits these Cleveland residents to pay the same school taxes as the Shaker residents, as well as vote in the Shaker school board elections.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] There are several private and parochial schools in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] These include Benedictine High School, Cleveland Central Catholic High School, Eleanor Gerson School, St.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is home to a number of colleges and universities.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Most prominent among them is Case Western Reserve University (CWRU), a widely recognized research and teaching institution based in University Circle with several major graduate programs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] University Circle also contains the Cleveland Institute of Art and the Cleveland Institute of Music.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Downtown Cleveland is home to Cleveland State University, a public research university with eight constituent colleges, and the metropolitan campus of Cuyahoga Community College.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Ohio Technical College is also based in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's suburban universities and colleges include Baldwin Wallace University in Berea, John Carroll University in University Heights, and Ursuline College in Pepper Pike.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Established in 1869, the Cleveland Public Library is one of the largest public libraries in the nation with a collection of over 13 million materials in 2023.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] It holds the Northeast Ohio Broadcast Archives, and the John G.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] White Special Collection, with the largest chess library in the world and a rare collection of folklore and books on the Middle East and Eurasia.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The library's main building was designed by Walker and Weeks and dedicated in 1925, under head librarian Linda Eastman, the first woman to lead a major library system in the U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Between 1904 and 1920, 15 libraries built with funds from Andrew Carnegie were opened in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Known as the "People's University", the library presently maintains 27 branches.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] It serves as the headquarters for the CLEVNET library consortium, which includes 47 public library systems in Northeast Ohio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's primary daily newspaper is *The Plain Dealer* and its associated online publication, *Cleveland.com*.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Defunct major newspapers include the *Cleveland Press* and the *Cleveland News*.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Additional publications include *Cleveland Magazine*, a regional culture magazine published monthly; *Crain's Cleveland Business*, a weekly business newspaper; and *Cleveland Scene*, a free alternative weekly paper which absorbed its competitor, the *Cleveland Free Times*, in 2008.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The digital *Belt Magazine* was founded in Cleveland in 2013.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] *Time* magazine was published in Cleveland from 1925 to 1927.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Several ethnic publications are based in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland-area television market is served by 11 full power stations, including WKYC (NBC), WEWS-TV (ABC), WJW (Fox), WDLI-TV (Bounce), WOIO (CBS), WVPX-TV (Ion), WVIZ (PBS), WUAB (MyNetworkTV), WRLM (TCT), WBNX-TV (CW), and WQHS-DT (Univision).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] As of 2021, the market, which includes the Akron and Canton areas, was the 19th-largest in the country, as measured by Nielsen Media Research.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is directly served by 29 full power AM and FM radio stations, 21 of which are licensed to the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] WMMS also serves as the FM flagship for the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians, WNCX is an FM flagship for the Cleveland Browns, and WJMO is the Spanish flagship for the Browns and Cavaliers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] News/talk stations include WHK, WTAM, and WERE.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] During the Golden Age of Radio, WHK was the first radio station to broadcast in Ohio, and one of the first in the country.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] WTAM is the AM flagship for both the Cleveland Cavaliers and the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Sports stations include WKNR (ESPN), WARF (Fox/VSiN) and WKRK-FM (WW1), with WKNR and WKRK-FM serving as co-flagship stations for the Cleveland Browns, and WARF – though primarily an English language station – airing Spanish broadcasts of Cleveland Guardians home games.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Religious stations include WHKW, WCCR, and WCRF.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] As the regional NPR affiliate, WKSU serves all of Northeast Ohio (including both the Cleveland and Akron markets).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] College stations include WBWC (Baldwin Wallace), WJCU (John Carroll), and WRUW-FM (Case Western Reserve).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland has a bus and rail mass transit system operated by the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority (RTA).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The rail portion is officially called the RTA Rapid Transit, but local residents refer to it as *The Rapid*.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] It consists of three light rail lines, known as the Blue, Green, and Waterfront Lines, and a heavy rail line, the Red Line.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2008, RTA completed the HealthLine, a bus rapid transit line, for which naming rights were purchased by the Cleveland Clinic and University Hospitals.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] It runs along Euclid Avenue from downtown through University Circle, ending at the Louis Stokes Station at Windermere in East Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 1968, Cleveland became the first city in the nation to have a direct rail transit connection linking the city's downtown to its major airport.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2021, Walk Score ranked Cleveland the 17th most walkable of the 50 largest cities in the U.S., with a Walk Score of 57, a Transit Score of 45, and a Bike Score of 55 (out of a maximum of 100).
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's most walkable areas can be found in the Downtown, Ohio City, Detroit–Shoreway, University Circle, and Buckeye–Shaker neighborhoods.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Like other major cities, the urban density of Cleveland reduces the need for private vehicle ownership.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In 2016, 23.7% of Cleveland households lacked a car, while the national average was 8.7%.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland averaged 1.19 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland's road system consists of numbered streets running roughly north–south, and named avenues, which run roughly east–west.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The numbered streets are designated "east" or "west", depending on where they lie in relation to Ontario Street, which bisects Public Square.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The two downtown avenues which span the Cuyahoga change names on the west side of the river.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Superior Avenue becomes Detroit Avenue on the West Side, and Carnegie Avenue becomes Lorain Avenue.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The bridges that make these connections are the Hope Memorial (Lorain–Carnegie) Bridge and the Veterans Memorial (Detroit–Superior) Bridge.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is served by three two-digit interstate highways – I-71, I-77, and I-90 – and by two three-digit interstates – I-480 and I-490.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Running due east–west through the West Side suburbs, I-90 turns northeast at the junction with I-490, and is known as the Cleveland Inner Belt.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Memorial Shoreway carries SR 2 along its length, and at varying points carries US 6, US 20 and I-90.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] At the junction with the Shoreway, I-90 makes a 90-degree turn in the area known as Dead Man's Curve, then continues northeast.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Jennings Freeway (SR 176) connects I-71 just south of I-90 to I-480.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] A third highway, the Berea Freeway (SR 237 in part), connects I-71 to the airport and forms part of the boundary between Brook Park and Cleveland's Hopkins neighborhood.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland is a major North American air market, serving 4.93 million people.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland Hopkins International Airport is the city's primary major airport and an international airport that serves the broader region.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Originally known as Cleveland Municipal Airport, it was the first municipally owned airport in the country.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland Hopkins is a significant regional air freight hub hosting FedEx Express, UPS Airlines, U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Postal Service, and major commercial freight carriers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition to Hopkins, Cleveland is served by Burke Lakefront Airport, on the north shore of downtown between Lake Erie and the Shoreway.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Burke is primarily a commuter and business airport.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Port of Cleveland, at the Cuyahoga River's mouth, is a major bulk freight and container terminal on Lake Erie, receiving much of the raw materials used by the region's manufacturing industries.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Port of Cleveland is the only container port on the Great Lakes with bi-weekly container service between Cleveland and the Port of Antwerp in Belgium on a Dutch service called the Cleveland-Europe Express.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition to freight, the Port of Cleveland welcomes regional and international tourists who pass through the city on Great Lakes cruises.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland has a long history as a major railroad hub in North America.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Today, Amtrak provides service to Cleveland, via the *Capitol Limited* and *Lake Shore Limited* routes, which stop at Cleveland Lakefront Station.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Additionally, Cleveland hosts several inter-modal freight railroad terminals, for Norfolk Southern, CSX and several smaller companies.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] National intercity bus service is provided by Greyhound from its downtown bus station.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Akron Metro, Brunswick Transit Alternative, Laketran, Lorain County Transit, and Medina County Transit provide connecting bus service to the Greater Cleveland Regional Transit Authority.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Geauga County Transit and Portage Area Regional Transportation Authority (PARTA) also offer connecting bus service in their neighboring areas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Cleveland maintains cultural, economic, and educational ties with 27 sister cities around the world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] It concluded its first sister city partnership with Lima, Peru, in 1964.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In addition, Cleveland hosts the Consulate General of the Republic of Slovenia, which, until Slovene independence in 1991, served as an official consulate for Tito's Yugoslavia.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Clinic operates the Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi hospital, two outpatient clinics in Toronto, and a hospital campus in London.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] The Cleveland Council on World Affairs was established in 1923.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Historically, Cleveland industrialist Cyrus S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] Rockefeller, played a significant role in promoting dialogue between the U.S. and the Soviet Union during the Cold War.
[src:cleveland-ohio/cleveland-ohio-p02] In October 1915 at Cleveland's Bohemian National Hall, Czech American and Slovak American representatives signed the Cleveland Agreement, calling for the formation of a joint Czech and Slovak state.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Both Dallas and Fort Worth were initially developed as a product of the construction of major railroad lines through the area allowing access to cotton, cattle, and later oil in North and East Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The construction of the Interstate Highway System reinforced Dallas's prominence as a transportation hub, with four major interstate highways converging in the city and a fifth interstate loop around it.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas then developed as a strong industrial and financial center and a major inland port, due to the convergence of major railroad lines, interstate highways, and the construction of Dallas Fort Worth International Airport, one of the largest and busiest airports in the world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In addition, Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) operates rail and bus transit services throughout the city and its surrounding suburbs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dominant sectors of its diverse economy include defense, financial services (such as traditional banking, investment banking, private equity, and venture capital), information technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex hosts 23 *Fortune* 500 companies, the second-most in Texas and fourth-most in the United States, and 11 of those companies are located within Dallas city limits.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Over 41 colleges and universities are located within its metropolitan area, which is the most of any metropolitan area in Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The city has a population from a myriad of ethnic and religious backgrounds.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Indigenous tribes in North Texas included the Caddo, Tawakoni, Wichita, Kickapoo and Comanche.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Spanish colonists claimed the territory of Texas in the 18th century as a part of the Viceroyalty of New Spain.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Later, France also claimed the area but never established much settlement.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In all, six flags have flown over the area preceding and during the city's history: those of France, Spain, and Mexico, the flag of the Republic of Texas, the Confederate flag, and the flag of the United States of America.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 1819, the Adams–Onís Treaty between the United States and Spain defined the Red River as the northern boundary of New Spain, officially placing the future location of Dallas well within Spanish territory.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The area remained under Spanish rule until 1821, when Mexico declared independence from Spain, and the area was considered part of the Mexican state of Coahuila y Tejas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 1836, Texians, with a majority of Anglo-American settlers, gained independence from Mexico and formed the Republic of Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Three years after Texas achieved independence, John Neely Bryan surveyed the area around present-day Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 1839, accompanied by his dog and a Cherokee he called Ned, he planted a stake in the ground on a bluff located near three forks of the Trinity River and left.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Two years later, in 1841, he returned to establish a permanent settlement named Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The official historical marker states it was named after Vice President George M.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Other potential theories for the origin include his brother, Commodore Alexander James Dallas, as well as brothers Walter R.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] A further theory gives the ultimate origin as the village of Dallas, Moray, Scotland, similar to the way Houston, Texas, was named after Sam Houston, whose ancestors came from the Scottish village of Houston, Renfrewshire.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Republic of Texas was annexed by the United States in 1845 and Dallas County was established the following year.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas was formally incorporated as a city on February 2, 1856.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In the mid-1800s, a group of French Socialists established La Réunion, a short-lived community, along the Trinity River in what is now West Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] With the construction of railroads, Dallas became a business and trading center and was booming by the end of the 19th century.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] It became an industrial city, attracting workers from Texas, the South, and the Midwest.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Praetorian Building in Dallas of 15 stories, built in 1909, was among the first skyscrapers west of the Mississippi and the tallest building in Texas for some time.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] It marked the prominence of Dallas as a city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] A racetrack for thoroughbreds was built and their owners established the Dallas Jockey Club.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Trotters raced at a track in Fort Worth, where a similar drivers club was based.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The rapid expansion of population increased competition for jobs and housing.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 1910, a white mob of hundreds of people lynched a black man, Allen Brooks, accused of raping a little girl.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The mob tortured Brooks, then killed him at the downtown intersection of Main and Akard by hanging him from a decorative archway inscribed with the words "Welcome Visitors".
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Thousands of Dallasites came to gawk at the torture scene, collecting keepsakes and posing for photographs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 1921, the Mexican president Álvaro Obregón along with the former revolutionary general visited Downtown Dallas's Mexican Park in Little Mexico; the small park was on the corner of Akard and Caruth Street, site of the current Fairmont Hotel.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The small neighborhood of Little Mexico was home to a Latin American population that had been drawn to Dallas by factors including the American Dream, better living conditions, and the Mexican Revolution.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Despite the onset of the Great Depression, business in construction was flourishing in 1930.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] That year, Columbus Marion "Dad" Joiner struck oil 100 miles (160 km) east of Dallas in Kilgore, spawning the East Texas oil boom.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas quickly became the financial center for the oil industry in Texas and Oklahoma.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] During World War II, Dallas was a major manufacturing center for military automobiles and aircraft for the United States and Allied forces.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Over 94,000 jeeps and over 6,000 military trucks were produced at the Ford plant in East Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] North American Aviation manufactured over 18,000 aircraft at their plant in Dallas, including the T-6 Texan trainer, P-51 Mustang fighter, and B-24 Liberator bomber.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] On November 22, 1963, United States President John F.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Kennedy was assassinated on Elm Street while his motorcade passed through Dealey Plaza in Downtown Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The upper two floors of the building from which the Warren Commission reported assassin Lee Harvey Oswald shot Kennedy have been converted into a historical museum covering the former president's life and accomplishments.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Kennedy was pronounced dead at Dallas Parkland Memorial Hospital just over 30 minutes after the shooting.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] On July 7, 2016, multiple shots were fired at a Black Lives Matter protest in Downtown Dallas, held against the police killings of two black men from other states.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The gunman, later identified as Micah Xavier Johnson, began firing at police officers at 8:58 p.m., killing five officers and injuring nine.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] This marked the deadliest day for U.S. law enforcement since the September 11 attacks.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Johnson told police during a standoff that he was upset about recent police shootings of black men and wanted to kill whites, especially white officers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] After hours of negotiation failed, police resorted to a robot-delivered bomb, killing Johnson inside Dallas College El Centro Campus.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The shooting occurred in an area of hotels, restaurants, businesses, and residential apartments only a few blocks away from Dealey Plaza.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas is situated in the Southern United States, in North Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] It is the county seat of Dallas County and portions of the city extend into neighboring Collin, Denton, Kaufman, and Rockwall counties.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Many suburbs surround Dallas; three enclaves are within the city boundaries—Cockrell Hill, Highland Park, and University Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 385.8 square miles (999.3 km2); 340.5 square miles (881.9 km2) of Dallas is land and 45.3 square miles (117.4 km2) of it (11.75%) is water.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas makes up one-fifth of the much larger urbanized area known as the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex, in which one quarter of all Texans live.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas's skyline has twenty buildings classified as skyscrapers, over 490 feet (150 m) in height.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Despite its tallest building not reaching 980 feet (300 m), Dallas does have a signature building in Bank of America Plaza which is lit up in neon but falls outside the top two hundred tallest buildings in the world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Although some of Dallas's architecture dates from the late 19th and early 20th centuries, most of the notable architecture in the city is from the modernist and postmodernist eras.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Iconic examples of modernist architecture include Reunion Tower, the John Fitzgerald Kennedy Memorial, I.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Pei's Dallas City Hall and the Morton H.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Good examples of postmodernist skyscrapers are Fountain Place, Bank of America Plaza, Renaissance Tower, JPMorgan Chase Tower, and Comerica Bank Tower.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Downtown Dallas also has residential offerings in downtown, some of which are signature skyline buildings.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Several smaller structures are fashioned in the Gothic Revival style, such as the Kirby Building, and the neoclassical style, as seen in the Davis and Wilson Buildings.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] One architectural "hotbed" in the city is a stretch of historic houses along Swiss Avenue, which has all shades and variants of architecture from Victorian to neoclassical.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Dallas Downtown Historic District protects a cross-section of Dallas commercial architecture from the 1880s to the 1940s.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The city of Dallas is home to many areas, neighborhoods, and communities.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas can be divided into several geographical areas which include larger geographical sections of territory including many subdivisions or neighborhoods, forming macroneighborhoods.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Central Dallas is anchored by Downtown Dallas, the center of the city, along with Oak Lawn and Uptown, areas characterized by dense retail, restaurants, and nightlife.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Downtown Dallas has a variety of named districts, including the West End Historic District, the Arts District, the Main Street District, Farmers Market District, the City Center Business District, the Convention Center District, and the Reunion District.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] This area includes Uptown, Victory Park, Harwood, Oak Lawn, Dallas Design District, Trinity Groves, Turtle Creek, Cityplace, Knox/Henderson, Greenville, and West Village.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Its historic district has one of the largest collections of Frank Lloyd Wright-inspired prairie-style homes in the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In the northeast quadrant of the city is Lake Highlands, one of Dallas's most unified middle-class neighborhoods.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Once a separate city founded in the mid-1800s, Oak Cliff was annexed in 1903 by Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] As one of the oldest areas in Dallas, the hilly North Oak Cliff is home to 5 of the 13 conservation districts in Dallas including the architecturally significant Kessler Park neighborhood and trendy Bishop Arts District.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] South Dallas is the location of Cedars, and Fair Park, where the annual State Fair of Texas is held from late September through mid-October.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Also located here is Exposition Park, Dallas, noted for having artists, art galleries, and bars along tree-lined Exposition Avenue.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] South Side Dallas is a popular location for nightly entertainment.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The neighborhood has undergone extensive development and community integration.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] What was once an area characterized by high rates of poverty and crime is now one of the city's most attractive social and living destinations.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Further east, in the southeast quadrant of the city, is the large neighborhood of Pleasant Grove.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Once an independent city, it is a collection of mostly lower-income residential areas stretching to Seagoville in the southeast.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Though a city neighborhood, Pleasant Grove is surrounded by undeveloped land on all sides.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Swampland and wetlands separating it from South Dallas are part of the Great Trinity Forest, a subsection of the city's Trinity River Project, newly appreciated for habitat and flood control.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas and its surrounding area are mostly flat.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The city lies at elevations ranging from 450 to 550 feet (137 to 168 m) above sea level.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The western edge of the Austin Chalk Formation, a limestone escarpment (also known as the "White Rock Escarpment"), rises 230 feet (70 m) and runs roughly north–south through Dallas County.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] South of the Trinity River, the uplift is particularly noticeable in the neighborhoods of Oak Cliff and the adjacent cities of Cockrell Hill, Cedar Hill, Grand Prairie, and Irving.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Marked variations in terrain are also found in cities immediately to the west in Tarrant County surrounding Fort Worth, as well as along Turtle Creek north of Downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas, like many other cities, was founded along a river.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The city was founded at the location of a "white rock crossing" of the Trinity River, where it was easier for wagons to cross the river in the days before ferries or bridges.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Trinity River, though not usefully navigable, is the major waterway through the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] I-35E parallels its path through Dallas along the Stemmons Corridor, then south alongside the western portion of Downtown and past South Dallas and Pleasant Grove, where the river is paralleled by Interstate 45 until it exits the city and heads southeast towards Houston.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The river is flanked on both sides by 50 feet (15 m) tall earthen levees to protect the city from frequent floods.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The project area reaches for over 20 miles (32 km) in length within the city, while the overall geographical land area addressed by the Land Use Plan is approximately 44,000 acres (180 km2) in size—about 20% of the land area in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Green space along the river encompasses approximately 10,000 acres (40 km2), making it one of the largest and diverse urban parks in the world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] White Rock Lake and Joe Pool Lake are reservoirs that comprise Dallas's other significant water features.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Built at the beginning of the 20th century, White Rock Lake Park is a popular destination for boaters, rowers, joggers, and bikers, as well as visitors seeking peaceful respite from the city at the 66-acre (267,000 m2) Dallas Arboretum and Botanical Garden, on the lake's eastern shore.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] White Rock Creek feeds into White Rock Lake and then exits into the Trinity River southeast of Downtown Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Trails along White Rock Creek are part of the extensive Dallas County Trails System.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Bachman Lake, just northwest of Love Field Airport, is a smaller lake also popularly used for recreation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Northeast of the city is Lake Ray Hubbard, a vast 22,745-acre (92 km2) reservoir in an extension of Dallas surrounded by the suburbs of Garland, Rowlett, Rockwall, and Sunnyvale.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] To the west of the city is Mountain Creek Lake, once home to the Naval Air Station Dallas (Hensley Field) and a number of defense aircraft manufacturers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfa*, Trewartha: *Cfhk*) characteristic of the Southern Plains of the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] It also has both continental and tropical characteristics, characterized by a relatively wide annual temperature range for the latitude.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Located at the lower end of Tornado Alley, it is prone to extreme weather, tornadoes, and hailstorms.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Summers in Dallas are very hot with high humidity, although extended periods of dry weather often occur.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] July and August are typically the hottest months, with an average high of 96.0 °F (36 °C) and an average low of 76.7 °F (25 °C).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Heat indices regularly surpass 105 °F (41 °C) due to elevated humidity during the summer months, making the summer heat almost unbearable.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The all-time record high is 113 °F (45 °C), set on June 26 and 27, 1980 during the Heat Wave of 1980 at nearby Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Winters in Dallas are usually mild, with occasional cold spells.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The average date of first frost is November 12, and the average date of last frost is March 12.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] January is typically the coldest month, with an average daytime high of 56.8 °F (14 °C) and an average nighttime low of 37.3 °F (3 °C).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Snow accumulation is seen in the city in about 70% of winter seasons, and snowfall generally occurs 1–2 days out of the year for a seasonal average of 1.5 inches (4 cm).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Some areas in the region, however, receive more than that, while other areas receive negligible snowfall or none at all.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The all-time record low temperature within the city is −10 °F (−23 °C), set on February 12, 1899, during the Great Blizzard of 1899.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The temperature at nearby Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport reached −2 °F (−19 °C) on February 16, 2021, during the February 2021 North American winter storm.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Spring and autumn are transitional seasons with moderate and pleasant weather.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Vibrant wildflowers (such as the bluebonnet, Indian paintbrush and other flora) bloom in spring and are planted around the highways throughout Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Springtime weather can be quite volatile, but temperatures themselves are mild.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Late spring to early summer also tends to be the most humid, with humidity levels frequently exceeding 75%.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The weather in Dallas is also generally pleasant from late September to early December and on many winter days.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Autumn often brings more storms and tornado threats, but they are usually fewer and less severe than in spring.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Each spring, cold fronts moving south from the North collide with warm, humid air streaming in from the Gulf Coast, leading to severe thunderstorms with lightning, torrents of rain, hail, and occasionally, tornadoes.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Over time, tornadoes have probably been the most significant natural threat to the city, as it is near the heart of Tornado Alley.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] A few times each winter in Dallas, warm and humid air from the south will override cold, dry air, resulting in freezing rain or ice and causing disruptions in the city if the roads and highways become slick.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Temperatures reaching 70 °F (21 °C) on average occur on at least four days each winter month.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas averages 26 annual nights at or below freezing, with the winter of 1999–2000 holding the record for the fewest freezing nights with 14.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] During this same span of 15 years, the temperature in the region has only twice dropped below 15 °F (−9 °C), though it will generally fall below 20 °F (−7 °C) in most (67%) years.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Department of Agriculture places Dallas in Plant Hardiness Zone 8b.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] However, mild winter temperatures in the past 15 to 20 years had encouraged the horticulture of more cold-sensitive plants such as *Washingtonia filifera* and *Washingtonia filifera var. robusta* palms, nearly all of which died off during the February 2021 North American winter storm.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] According to the American Lung Association, Dallas has the 12th highest air pollution among U.S. cities, ranking it behind Los Angeles and Houston.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Much of the air pollution in Dallas and the surrounding area comes from a hazardous materials incineration plant in the small town of Midlothian and from cement plants in neighboring Ellis County.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The average daily low in Dallas is 57.4 °F (14 °C), and the average daily high is 76.9 °F (25 °C).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas receives approximately 39.1 inches (993 mm) of rain per year.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The record snowfall for Dallas was 11.2 inches (28 cm) on February 11, 2010.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas is the ninth-most-populous city in the United States and third in Texas after the cities of Houston and San Antonio.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Its metropolitan area encompasses one-quarter of the population of Texas, and is the largest in the Southern U.S. and Texas followed by the Greater Houston metropolitan area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] At the 2020 United States census the city of Dallas had 1,304,379 residents, an increase of 106,563 since the 2010 United States census.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Census Bureau estimates that Dallas, in the first years since the 2020 census, lost 4,835 people, leaving the city with a population of 1,299,544.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] There were 524,498 households at the 2020 estimates, up from 2010's 458,057 households, out of which 137,523 had children under the age of 18 living with them.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Approximately 36.2% of households were headed by married couples living together, 57.2% had a single householder male or female with no spouse present, and 35.6% were classified as non-family households with the householder living alone.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 2010, 33.7% of all households had one or more people under 18 years of age, and 17.6% had one or more people who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The average household size in 2020 was 2.52 and the average family size was 3.41.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 2018, the owner-occupied housing rate was 40.2% and the renter-occupied housing rate was 59.8%.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] At the 2010 census, the city's age distribution of the population showed 26.5% under the age of 18 and 8.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 2010, 50.0% of the population was male and 50.0% was female.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 2020, the median age 32.9 years; for every 100 females, there were 98.4 males.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the median income for a household in the city was $54,747; families had a median household income of $60,895; married-couple families $81,761; and non-families $45,658.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 2003–2007's survey, male full-time workers had a median income of $32,265 versus $32,402 for female full-time workers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The per capita income for the city was $25,904.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] About 18.7% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 33.6% of those under age 18 and 13.4% of those aged 65 or over.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Per 2007's survey, the median price for a house was $129,600; by 2020, the median price for a house was valued at $252,300, with 54.4% of owner-occupied units from $50,000 to $299,999.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The 2022 Point-In-Time Homeless Count found there were 4,410 homeless people in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The region surrounding Dallas is a habitat for mosquitoes, creating a pest problem for humans.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas and the surrounding area is sprayed regularly to control mosquito-borne diseases such as West Nile virus.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas's population was historically predominantly White (non-Hispanic Whites made up 82.8% of the population in 1930), but its population has diversified due to immigration and white flight over the 20th century.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Since then, the non-Hispanic White population has declined to less than one-third of the city's population.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Census Bureau's 2019 estimates, 29.1% were non-Hispanic White 24.3% Black and African American, 0.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 3.7% Asian, and 1.4% from two or more races.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islanders made up a total of 312 residents according to 2019's census estimates, down from 606 in 2017.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Hispanic or Latino Americans of any race made up 41.2% of the estimated population in 2019.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Among the Hispanic or Latino American population in 2019, 34.6% of Dallas was Mexican, 0.4% Puerto Rican, 0.2% Cuban and 6.0% other Hispanic or Latino American.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 2017's American Community Survey estimates among the demographic 35.5% were Mexican, 0.6% Puerto Rican, 0.4% Cuban, and 5.4% other Hispanic or Latino.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] By 2020, Hispanic or Latino Americans of any race continued to constitute the largest ethnic group in the city proper, reflecting nationwide demographic trends.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Dallas area is a major living destination for Mexican Americans and other Hispanic and Latino American immigrants.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The southwestern portion of the city, particularly Oak Cliff is chiefly inhabited by Hispanic and Latino American residents.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The southeastern portion of the city Pleasant Grove is chiefly inhabited by African American and Hispanic or Latino American residents, while the southern portion of the city is predominantly black.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The west and east sides of the city are predominantly Hispanic or Latino American; Garland also has a large Spanish-speaking population.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] North Dallas has many enclaves of predominantly white, black and especially Hispanic or Latino American residents.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Dallas area is also a major living destination for Black and African Americans primarily due to its strong and diverse economy.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Between 2010 and 2020, the Dallas area had the second-most new Black and African American residents only behind the Atlanta area and slightly above the Houston area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The notable influx of African Americans is partly due to the New Great Migration.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] There is a significant number of people from the Horn of Africa, immigrants from Ethiopia, Eritrea and Somalia.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Dallas–Fort-Worth metroplex had an estimated 70,000 Russian-speakers (as of November 6, 2012) mostly immigrants from the former Soviet Bloc.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Included in this population are Russians, Russian Jews, Ukrainians, Armenians, Belarusians, Moldavians Uzbek, Kirghiz, and others.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Russian-speaking population of Dallas has continued to grow in the sector of "American husbands-Russian wives".
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Russian DFW has its own newspaper, *The Dallas Telegraph*.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In addition, Dallas and its suburbs are home to a large number of Asian Americans including those of Indian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Korean, Filipino, Japanese, and other heritage.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Among large-sized cities in the United States, Plano, the northern suburb of Dallas, has the 6th largest Chinese American population as of 2016.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Plano-Richardson area in particular had an estimated 30,000 Iranian Americans in 2012.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] With so many immigrant groups, there are often multilingual signs in the linguistic landscape.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Census Bureau data released in December 2013, 23 percent of Dallas County residents were foreign-born, while 16 percent of Tarrant County residents were foreign-born.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The 2018 census estimates determined that the city of Dallas's foreign-born population consisted of 25.4% naturalized citizens and 74.6% non-citizens.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas and the Metroplex have one of the largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) populations in the country.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Throughout the year there are LGBT events held in the area, including the annual Alan Ross Texas Freedom (Pride) Parade and Festival in June, which draws approximately 50,000 attendees.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] For decades, the Oak Lawn and Bishop Arts districts have been known as the epicenters of LGBT culture in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Dallas and the wider metropolitan area according to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center (78%), and the Public Religion Research Institute's 2020 study (77%).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] There is a large Protestant Christian influence in the Dallas community, though the city of Dallas and Dallas County have more Catholic than Protestant residents, while the reverse is usually true for the suburban areas of Dallas and the city of Fort Worth.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas has been called the "Prison Ministry Capital of the World" by the prison ministry community.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] It is a home for the International Network of Prison Ministries, the Coalition of Prison Evangelists, Bill Glass Champions for Life, Chaplain Ray's International Prison Ministry, and 60 other prison ministries.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Methodist, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches are prominent in many neighborhoods and anchor two of the city's major private universities (Southern Methodist University and Dallas Baptist University).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas is also home to two evangelical seminaries: the Dallas Theological Seminary and Criswell College.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Many Bible schools including Christ For The Nations Institute are also headquartered in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Christian creationist apologetics group Institute for Creation Research is headquartered in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] According to the Pew Research Center, evangelical Protestantism constituted the largest form of Protestantism in the area as of 2014.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The largest single evangelical Protestant group were Baptists.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The largest Baptist denomination was the Southern Baptist Convention, followed by the historically black National Baptist Convention USA.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] African-initiated Protestant churches including Ethiopian Evangelical churches can be found throughout the metropolitan area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Catholic Church is also a significant religious organization in the Dallas area and operates the University of Dallas, a liberal-arts university in the Dallas suburb of Irving.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Cathedral Santuario de la Virgen de Guadalupe in the Arts District is home to the second-largest Catholic church membership in the United States and overseas, consisting over 70 parishes in the Dallas Diocese.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Society of Jesus operates the Jesuit College Preparatory School of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas is also home to numerous Eastern Orthodox and Oriental Orthodox churches including Saint Seraphim Cathedral, see of the Orthodox Church in America's Southern Diocese.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America (Ecumenical Patriarchate) has one parish in the city of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Sarkis Armenian Church (serving as part of the Armenian Apostolic Church facility).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Jehovah's Witnesses has a large number of members throughout the Dallas metropolitan division.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In addition, there are several Unitarian Universalist congregations, including First Unitarian Church of Dallas, founded in 1899.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] A large community of the United Church of Christ exists in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The most prominent UCC-affiliated church is the Cathedral of Hope, a predominantly LGBT-affirming church.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has a sizeable community in the Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Members in the area are organized into 24 stakes.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The Dallas Texas Temple, dedicated in 1984 as the first temple in Texas, is located in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Two more temples, the Fort Worth Texas Temple and Fairview Texas Temple, are under construction in the area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Since the establishment of the city's first Jewish cemetery in 1854 and its first congregation (which would eventually be known as Temple Emanu-El) in 1873, Dallasite Jews have been well represented among leaders in commerce, politics, and various professional fields in Dallas and elsewhere.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Furthermore, a large Muslim community exists in the north and northeastern portions of Dallas, as well as in the northern Dallas suburbs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] The oldest mosque in Dallas is Masjid Al-Islam just south of Downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Immigrants from East Asia, Southeast Asia, Nepal, and Sri Lanka have all contributed to the Buddhist population, which is concentrated in the northern suburbs of Garland, Plano and Richardson.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Numerous Buddhist temples dot the Metroplex including The Buddhist Center of Dallas, Lien Hoa Vietnamese Temple of Irving, and Kadampa Meditation Center Texas and Wat Buddhamahamunee of Arlington.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] A large and growing Hindu Community lives in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Most live in Collin County and the northern portions of Dallas County.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Over 28 Hindu Temples exist in the area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Some notable ones include the DFW Hindu Temple, the North Texas Hindu Mandir, Radha Krishna Temple, Dallas and Karya Siddhi Hanuman Temple.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] There are also at least three Sikh Gurudwaras in this metropolitan area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] For irreligious people, the Winter Solstice Celebration is held in the Metroplex although some of its participants are also neo-pagans and New Agers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] According to the FBI, a city to city comparison of crime rates can be misleading, because recording practices vary from city to city, citizens report different percentages of crimes from one city to the next, and the actual number of people physically present in a city is unknown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] With that in mind, Dallas has one of the top 10 crime rates in Texas and its crime rate is higher than the national average.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Since 2020, Dallas's murder rate has seen a notable increase.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] In 2020, Dallas recorded 251 murders which was a 20-year high.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] By 2022 it decreased to 214 but then increased to 246 in 2023.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] As of 2020, the gang presence in Dallas has grown significantly and is heavily responsible for the spike in crime.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p01] Dallas leaders have made crime reduction a major priority.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In its beginnings, Dallas relied on farming, neighboring Fort Worth's Stockyards, and its prime location on Native American trade routes to sustain itself.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas's key to growth came in 1873 with the construction of multiple rail lines through the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] As Dallas grew and technology developed, cotton became its boon and by 1900, Dallas was the largest inland cotton market in the world, becoming a leader in cotton gin machinery manufacturing.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] By the early 1900s, Dallas was a hub for economic activity all over the Southern United States and was selected in 1914 as the seat of the Eleventh Federal Reserve District.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] By 1925, Texas churned out more than 1⁄3 of the nation's cotton crop, with 31% of Texas cotton produced within a 100-mile (160 km) radius of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In the 1930s, petroleum was discovered east of Dallas, near Kilgore.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas's proximity to the discovery put it immediately at the center of the nation's petroleum market.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Petroleum discoveries in the Permian Basin, the Panhandle, the Gulf Coast, and Oklahoma in the following years further solidified Dallas's position as the hub of the market.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The end of World War II left Dallas seeded with a nexus of communications, engineering, and production talent by companies such as Collins Radio Corporation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Decades later, the telecommunications and information revolutions still drive a large portion of the local economy.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The city is sometimes referred to as the heart of "Silicon Prairie" because of a high concentration of telecommunications companies in the region, the epicenter of which lies along the Telecom Corridor in Richardson, a northern suburb of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Texas Instruments, a major manufacturer, employs 10,400 people at its corporate headquarters and chip plants in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In the 1980s Dallas was a real estate hotbed, with the increasing metropolitan population bringing with it a demand for new housing and office space.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Several of Downtown Dallas's largest buildings are the fruit of this boom, but over-speculation, the savings and loan crisis and an oil bust brought the 1980s building boom to an end for Dallas as well as its sister city Houston.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Between the late 1980s and the early 2000s, central Dallas went through a slow period of growth.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] However, since the early 2000s the central core of Dallas has been enjoying steady and significant growth encompassing both repurposing of older commercial buildings in Downtown Dallas into residential and hotel uses, as well as the construction of new office and residential towers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The opening of Klyde Warren Park, built across Woodall Rodgers Freeway seamlessly connecting the central Dallas CBD to Uptown/Victory Park, has acted synergistically with the highly successful Dallas Arts District, so both have become catalysts for significant new development in central Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The residential real estate market in the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex has not only been resilient but has once again returned to a boom status.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas and the greater metro area have been leading the nation in apartment construction and net leasing, with rents reaching all-time highs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Single family home sales, whether pre-owned or new construction, along with home price appreciation, were leading the nation since 2015.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] A sudden drop in the price of oil, starting in mid-2014 and accelerating throughout 2015, has not significantly affected Dallas and its greater metro area due to the highly diversified nature of its economy.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas and the metropolitan region continue to see strong demand for housing, apartment and office leasing, shopping center space, warehouse and industrial space with overall job growth remaining very robust.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Oil-dependent cities and regions have felt significant effects from the downturn, but Dallas's growth has continued unabated, strengthening in 2015.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas–Fort Worth area has one of the largest concentrations of corporate headquarters for publicly traded companies in the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] *Fortune Magazine*'s 2022 annual list of the Fortune 500 in America indicates the city of Dallas had 11 Fortune 500 companies and the DFW region as a whole had 23.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] As of 2022, Dallas–Fort Worth represents the second-largest concentration of Fortune 500 headquarters in Texas and fourth-largest in the United States, behind the metropolitan areas of Houston (24), Chicago (35) and New York (62).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In 2008, AT&T relocated their headquarters to Downtown Dallas; AT&T is the largest telecommunications company in the world and was the ninth largest company in the nation by revenue for 2017.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In October 2016, Jacobs Engineering, one of the world's largest engineering companies, relocated from Pasadena, California to Downtown Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Nearby Irving is home to six Fortune 500 companies of its own, including McKesson, the country's largest pharmaceutical distributor and listed at number seven overall on the 2021 Fortune 500 list, Fluor (engineering), Kimberly-Clark, Celanese, Michaels Companies, and Vistra Energy.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Plano is home to an additional four Fortune 500 companies, including J.C.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Penney, Alliance Data Systems, Yum China, and Dr.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Fort Worth is home to two Fortune 500 companies, including American Airlines, the largest airline in the world by revenue, fleet size, profit, passengers carried and revenue passenger mile and D.R.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Horton, the largest homebuilder in America.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Westlake, TX, north of Fort Worth, now has two Fortune 500 companies: Financial services giant, Charles Schwab, and convenience store distributor, Core-Mark.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] One Fortune 500 company, GameStop, is based in Grapevine.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Cheese's, Zale Corporation, and Fossil, Inc.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Many of these companies—and others throughout the DFW metroplex—comprise the Dallas Regional Chamber.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Komen for the Cure, the world's largest breast cancer organization, was founded and is headquartered in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In addition to its large number of businesses, Dallas has more shopping centers per capita than any other city in the United States and is also home to the second shopping center ever built in the United States, Highland Park Village, which opened in 1931.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas is home of the two other major malls in North Texas, the Dallas Galleria and NorthPark Center, which is the second largest mall in Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Both malls feature high-end stores and are major tourist draws for the region.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Tourism is an important sector of Dallas's economy and is its tenth largest employer, providing 56,000 jobs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas receives on average 25 million visitors annually.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Arts District in the northern section of Downtown is home to several arts venues and is the largest contiguous arts district in the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Notable venues in the district include the Dallas Museum of Art; the Morton H.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Meyerson Symphony Center, home to the Dallas Symphony Orchestra and Dallas Wind Symphony; the Nasher Sculpture Center; and the Trammell & Margaret Crow Collection of Asian Art.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Perot Museum of Nature and Science, also in Downtown Dallas, is a natural history and science museum.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Designed by 2005 Pritzker Architecture Prize Laureate Thom Mayne and his firm Morphosis Architects, the 180,000-square-foot (17,000 m2) facility has six floors and stands about 14 stories high.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Not far north of the area is the Meadows Museum at Southern Methodist University.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In 2009, it joined up with Madrid's Prado Museum for a three-year partnership.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Prado focuses on Spanish visual art and has a collection of Spanish art in North America, with works by de Juanes, El Greco, Fortuny, Goya, Murillo, Picasso, Pkensa, Ribera, Rico, Velasquez, Zurbaran, and other Spaniards.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] These works, as well as non-Spanish highlights like sculptures by Rodin and Moore, have been so successful of a collaboration that the Prado and Meadows have agreed upon an extension of the partnership.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The former Texas School Book Depository, from which, according to the Warren Commission Report, Lee Harvey Oswald shot and killed President John F.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Kennedy in 1963, has served since the 1980s as a county government office building, except for its sixth and seventh floors, which house the Sixth Floor Museum.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The American Museum of the Miniature Arts is at the Hall of State in Fair Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Arts District is also home to DISD's Booker T.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Washington High School for the Performing and Visual Arts, a magnet school that was recently expanded.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] City Center District, next to the Arts District, is home to the Dallas Contemporary.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Institute for Creation Research operates the ICR Discovery Center for Science & Earth History, a creationism museum, in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Deep Ellum, immediately east of Downtown, originally became popular during the 1920s and 1930s as the prime jazz and blues hot spot in the South.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Artists such as Blind Lemon Jefferson, Robert Johnson, Huddie "Lead Belly" Ledbetter, and Bessie Smith played in original Deep Ellum clubs such as the Harlem and the Palace.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Today, Deep Ellum is home to hundreds of artists who live in lofts or operate in studios throughout the district alongside bars, pubs, and concert venues.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] A major art infusion in the area results from the city's lax stance on graffiti, and a number of public spaces, including tunnels, sides of buildings, sidewalks, and streets, are covered in murals.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] One major example, the Good-Latimer tunnel, was torn down in late 2006 to accommodate the construction of a light rail line through the site.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Like Deep Ellum before it, the Cedars neighborhood to the south of Downtown has also seen a growing population of studio artists and an expanding roster of entertainment venues.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The area's art scene began to grow in the early 2000s with the opening of Southside on Lamar, an old Sears Roebuck and Company warehouse converted into lofts, studios, and retail.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Current attractions include Gilley's Dallas and Poor David's Pub.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas Mavericks owner and local entrepreneur Mark Cuban purchased land along Lamar Street near Cedars Station in September 2005, and locals speculate he is planning an entertainment complex for the site.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] South of the Trinity River, the Bishop Arts District in Oak Cliff is home to a number of studio artists living in converted warehouses.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Walls of buildings along alleyways and streets are painted with murals, and the surrounding streets contain many eclectic restaurants and shops.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas has an Office of Cultural Affairs as a department of the city government.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The office is responsible for six cultural centers throughout the city, funding for local artists and theaters, initiating public art projects, and running the city-owned classical radio station WRR.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Los Angeles-class submarine USS *Dallas* was planned to become a museum ship near the Trinity River after her decommissioning in September 2014, but this has since been delayed.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] It will be taken apart into massive sections in Houston and be transported by trucks to the museum site and will be put back together.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The city is served by the Dallas Public Library system.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The system was created by the Dallas Federation of Women's Clubs with efforts spearheaded by then president May Dickson Exall.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Her fundraising efforts led to a grant from philanthropist and steel baron Andrew Carnegie, which allowed the library system to build its first branch in 1901.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Today, the library operates 30 branch locations throughout the city, including the 8-story J.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Erik Jonsson Central Library in the Government District of Downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas is known for its barbecue, authentic Mexican, and Tex-Mex cuisine.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Famous products of the Dallas culinary scene include the Frozen margarita machine by restaurateur Mariano Martinez in 1971.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The State Fair of Texas has been held annually at Fair Park since 1886, and generates an estimated $50 million to the city's economy annually.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Red River Shootout, a football game that pits the University of Texas at Austin against the University of Oklahoma at the Cotton Bowl, also brings significant crowds to the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The city also hosts the State Fair Classic and Heart of Dallas Bowl at the Cotton Bowl.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] With the opening of Victory Park, WFAA began hosting an annual New Year's Eve celebration in AT&T Plaza that the television station hoped would be reminiscent of celebrations in New York's Times Square; New Year's Eve 2011 set a new record of 32,000 people in attendance.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] After the discontinuance of the "Big D NYE" festivities a few years later, a new end-of-year event was started downtown, with a big fireworks show put on at Reunion Tower, which has since aired on KXAS and other TV stations around the state and region.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Also, several Omni hotels in the Dallas area host large events to welcome in the new year, including murder mystery parties, rave-inspired events, and other events.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Downtown Dallas is home to two major league sports teams that play at the American Airlines Center: the Dallas Mavericks (NBA), who won the NBA Championship in 2011, and the Dallas Stars (NHL), who won the Stanley Cup in 1999.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Nearby Arlington is home to the Dallas Cowboys (NFL), who play at the AT&T Stadium and have won five Super Bowls, the Texas Rangers (MLB), who play at Globe Life Field and won the World Series in 2023, and the Dallas Wings (WNBA), who play at College Park Center.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] MLS team FC Dallas plays at Toyota Stadium in Frisco and won the Lamar Hunt U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The newest team in Dallas is Dallas Trinity FC, the first professional women's soccer team that plays at the historic Cotton Bowl (stadium).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The city is home to several minor league and college sports programs in the area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Since joining the league as an expansion team in 1960, the Cowboys have enjoyed substantial success, advancing to eight Super Bowls and winning five.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Cowboys are financially the most valuable sports franchise in the world, worth approximately $4 billion.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In 2009, they relocated to their new 80,000-seat stadium in Arlington, which was the site of Super Bowl XLV and is set to host the most matches during the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Cowboys are currently part of the East Division of the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Texas Rangers won the American League pennant in 2010, 2011 and 2023, and won the World Series in 2023.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The franchise relocated from Washington D.C. in 1972.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] They play in the West Division of the American League.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas Mavericks joined the league as an expansion team in 1980.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] They won their first National Basketball Association championship in 2011 led by Dirk Nowitzki.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] They play in the Southwest Division of the Western Conference.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas Stars moved to North Texas in 1993 as a relocation from the former team, the Minnesota North Stars.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Stars have won eight division titles in Dallas, two Presidents' Trophies as the top regular season team in the NHL, the Western Conference championship three times, and in 1998–99, the Stanley Cup.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The team plays in the Central Division of the Western Conference.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] FC Dallas play at Toyota Stadium (formerly FC Dallas Stadium and Pizza Hut Park), a stadium that opened in 2005.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] They currently play in MLS's Western Conference.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The team was originally called the Dallas Burn and used to play in the Cotton Bowl.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Although FC Dallas has not yet won a MLS Cup, they won the Lamar Hunt U.S.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Open Cup in 1997 and 2016 and the Supporters' Shield in 2016.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Previously, the Dallas Tornado played in the North American Soccer League from 1968 to 1981.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas Wings came to The Metroplex in 2016 after relocating from Tulsa.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] There are many notable minor league teams in the Dallas-Fort Worth.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Allen Americans are a professional ice hockey team headquartered at the Credit Union of Texas Event Center in Allen, Texas, which currently plays in the ECHL.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] They are the minor league affiliate of the NHL's Seattle Kraken.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The team was founded in 2009 in the Central Hockey League(CHL).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas Renegades are a professional football team in the UFL that plays their home games at Toyota Stadium.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas Sidekicks (2012) are an American professional indoor soccer team based in Allen, Texas, a suburb of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] They play their home games in the Credit Union of Texas Event Center.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The team is named after the original Dallas Sidekicks that operated from 1984 to 2004.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The MLS-affiliated North Texas SC team is a member of MLS Next Pro and plays in Frisco at Toyota Stadium; it is the reserve team of FC Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas Mavericks own an NBA G League team, the Texas Legends.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Rugby is a developing sport in Dallas and Texas in general.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The multiple clubs, ranging from men's and women's clubs to collegiate and high school, are part of the Texas Rugby Football Union.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas was one of only 16 cities in the United States included in the Rugby Super League, represented by Dallas Harlequins.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Australian rules football is also growing in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas Magpies, founded in 1998, compete in the United States Australian Football League.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The only Division I sports program within the Dallas political boundary is the Dallas Baptist University Patriots baseball team.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Although outside the city limits, the Mustangs of Southern Methodist University are in the enclave of University Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Neighboring cities Fort Worth, Arlington, and Denton are home to the Texas Christian University Horned Frogs, UT Arlington Mavericks, and University of North Texas Mean Green respectively.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas area hosted the Final Four of the 2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament at AT&T Stadium.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The college Cotton Bowl Classic football game was played at the Cotton Bowl through its 2009 game, but has moved to AT&T Stadium.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Red River Showdown is an American college football rivalry game played annually at the Cotton Bowl Stadium during the second weekend of the State Fair of Texas in October.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The game is played by the Oklahoma Sooners football team of the University of Oklahoma and the Texas Longhorns football team of the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The 10,000-capacity Forester Stadium, which is used mainly for football and soccer, is also located in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas Trinity FC is the first professional women's soccer team in Dallas that plays at the historic Cotton Bowl (stadium) located in Downtown Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Originally founded in May 2023 by the Neil family and managed by Chris Petrucelli, the club kicked off its inaugural season in August 2024 when they played Tampa Bay Sun FC, ending in a 1 v 1 tie.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Following this match was two very significant matches for the club, the friendly match and home opener.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The club played their friendly match vs FC Barcelona Femení where they lost 0-6 and the club's official home match was against DC Power FC where they tied 1-1.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The club finished the season 12–9–7, finishing third and getting eliminated by Tampa Bay Sun FC by the final score of 2–1 in the semi-finals of the USL Championship.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Following its inaugural season, the teams parted ways with Pauline MacDonald and Gavin Beith.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Recently, the team announced its State Fair Clasico Match during the Texas State Fair at Fair Park on October 18 vs Club América Femenil.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Major League Volleyball expanded to the Dallas market after announcing plans for a single, unified professional women's volleyball league with the former Pro Volleyball Federation (PVF) in 2025.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas franchise of Major League Volleyball was officially named Dallas Pulse and confirmed Comerica Center in Frisco as its home court for their 2026 debut.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In their inaugural season, the Pulse have clinched a postseason spot with Head Coach, Shannon Winzer, as they prepare to host the 2026 MLV Championship at Comerica Center.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas maintains and operates 406 parks on 21,000 acres (85 km2) of parkland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The city's parks contain 17 separate lakes, including White Rock and Bachman lakes, spanning a total of 4,400 acres (17.81 km2).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Built in 1936 for the Texas Centennial Exposition world's fair, Fair Park is the world's largest collection of Art Deco exhibit buildings, art, and sculptures; Fair Park is also home to the State Fair of Texas, the largest state fair in the United States with 2 million visitors.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In November 2019, consultants presented to the public a master plan to revitalize the area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Named after Klyde Warren, the young son of billionaire Kelcy Warren, the 5.2-acre Klyde Warren Park was built above Woodall Rodgers Freeway and connects Uptown and Downtown, specifically the Arts District.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Klyde Warren Park is home to an amphitheater, jogging trails, a children's park, a dog park, a putting green, croquet, ping pong, chess, an outdoor library, and two restaurants.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Food trucks give another option of dining and are lined along the park's Downtown side.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] There are also weekly planned events, including yoga, Zumba, skyline tours, tai chi, and meditation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Klyde Warren Park is home to a free trolley stop on Olive St., which riders can connect to Downtown, McKinney Avenue, and West Village.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Built in 1913, Turtle Creek Parkway park is a 23.7-acre (9.6 ha) linear park in between Turtle Creek and Turtle Creek Boulevard in the aptly named Turtle Creek neighborhood.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Archaeological surveys discovered dart points and flint chips dating 3,000 years to 1,000 BCE.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] This site was later discovered to be home to Native Americans who cherished the trees and natural spring water.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The park is across Turtle Creek from Kalita Humphreys Theater, designed by Frank Lloyd Wright.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Opened on July 4, 1906, Lake Cliff Park was called "the Southwest's Greatest Playground".
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The park was home to an amusement park, a large pool, waterslides, the world's largest skating rink, and three theaters, the largest being the 2,500-seat Casino Theater.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] After the streetcar bridge that brought most of the park visitors collapsed, Lake Cliff Park was sold.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Casino Theater moved and the pool was demolished after a polio scare in 1959.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The pool was Dallas's first municipal pool.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In 1935, Dallas purchased 36 acres (15 ha) from John Cole's estate to develop Reverchon Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Reverchon Park was named after botanist Julien Reverchon, who left France to live in the La Reunion colony, which was founded in the mid-1800s and was situated in present-day West Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Reverchon Park was planned to be the crown jewel of the Dallas park system and was even referred to as the "Central Park" of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Improvements were made throughout the years, including the Iris Bowl, picnic settings, a baseball diamond, and tennis courts.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Iris Bowl celebrated many Greek pageants, dances, and other performances.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Gill Well was installed for nearby residents and drew people all across Texas who wanted to experience the water's healing powers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The baseball diamond was host to a 1953 exhibition game for the New York Giants and the Cleveland Indians.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] As part of the ongoing Trinity River Project, the Great Trinity Forest, at 6,000 acres (24 km2), is the largest urban hardwood forest in the United States and is part of the largest urban park in the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Trinity River Audubon Center is a new addition to the park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Opened in 2008, it serves as a gateway to many trails and other nature-viewing activities in the area.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Trinity River Audubon Center is the first LEED-certified building built by the City of Dallas Parks and Recreation Department.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Named after its former railroad name, the Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad (or "MKT" Railroad), the 3.5-mile (5.6 km) stretch of railroad was purchased by the city of Dallas and transformed into the city's premier trail.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Stretching from Victory Park, the 30-acre (12 ha) Katy Trail passes through the Turtle Creek and Knox Park neighborhoods and runs along the east side of Highland Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The trail ends at Central Expressway, but extensions are underway to extend the trail to the White Rock Lake Trail in Lakewood.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas hosts three of the twenty-one preserves of the extensive 3,200 acres (13 km2) Dallas County Preserve System.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Joppa Preserve, the McCommas Bluff Preserve, and the Cedar Ridge Preserve are within the Dallas city limits.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Cedar Ridge Preserve was known as the Dallas Nature Center, but the Audubon Dallas group now manages the 633-acre (2.56 km2) natural habitat park on behalf of the city of Dallas and Dallas County.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The preserve sits at an elevation of 755 feet (230 m) above sea level and offers a variety of outdoor activities, including 10 miles (16 km) of hiking trails and picnic areas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The city is also home to Texas's first and largest zoo, the 106-acre (0.43 km2) Dallas Zoo, which opened at its current location in 1888.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The city uses a council-manager government, with Eric Johnson serving as mayor, Kimberly Tolbert serving as city manager, and 14 council members serving as representatives to the 14 council districts in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] This organizational structure was contested by some in favor of a strong-mayor city charter, only to be rejected by Dallas voters.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Martínez become the first Latin American to sit as a councilwoman in Dallas's city council.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In the 2017–2018 fiscal year, the city's total budget (the sum of operating and capital budgets) was $3.3 billion.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The United States District Court for the Northern District of Texas, which exercises original jurisdiction over 100 counties in North and West Texas, convenes in the Earle Cabell Federal Building and Courthouse in the Government District of Downtown.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The same building additionally houses United States Bankruptcy and Magistrate Courts and a United States Attorney office.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas also is the seat of the Fifth Court of Appeals of Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Since 2023, Dallas has been the largest city in the United States with a Republican mayor after Eric Johnson switched parties after winning re-election.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Democratic voters dominate the majority of the city, especially the central urban core and southern sectors, with Republicans spreading a sliver of suburban neighborhoods in North Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In the 2004 U.S. presidential election, 57% of voters in Dallas's city limits voted for John Kerry over George W.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas County was closely divided, with 50% of voters voting for Bush and 49% voting for Kerry.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Results in the 2008 and 2012 elections favored Barack Obama, with the 44th President receiving 57% of Dallas County voters in both years, with greater margins in the city of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In the 2016 U.S. presidential election, approximately 66% of Dallas voters voted for Hillary Clinton, with 28% of city voters voting for Donald Trump.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas County as a whole saw 61% of voters voting for Clinton, with 35% support for Trump.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In 2004, Lupe Valdez was elected Dallas County Sheriff.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] An open lesbian, Valdez was the only female sheriff in the state of Texas until her resignation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Despite controversies in her handling of county jails, she won re-election in 2008 with a 10-point victory over Republican challenger Lowell Cannaday.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In the 2024 United States presidential election, Donald Trump, achieved 34.1% of the vote in the city of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] This marked the highest level of support for a Republican candidate in the city since the 2012 election, when Mitt Romney received a comparable percentage.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Trump's performance in Dallas has been attributed in part to a notable shift in Hispanic voter preferences within Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Trump garnered an estimated 55% of the Hispanic vote statewide, a significant improvement from his performance among Hispanic voters in 2016.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] There are 337 public schools, 89 private schools, 38 colleges, and 32 libraries in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Dallas–Fort Worth is also home to six Nobel Laureates.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Dallas area has a high number of colleges and universities.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In addition to those in the city, the surrounding cities also have a number of universities, colleges, trade schools, and other educational institutions.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Texas Legislature defines all areas in Dallas County and in the Carrollton-Farmers Branch Independent School District as being in the service area of Dallas College (formerly Dallas County Community College District or DCCCD).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Areas in Collin County are assigned to Collin College.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Most areas in the city of Dallas are within the Dallas Independent School District, the 12th-largest school district in the United States and second largest in Texas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The school district operates independently of the city and enrolls over 161,000 students.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] As of 2003 DISD has the majority of K–12 students in the city of Dallas, and a proportionately larger number of students who are not non-Hispanic white.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] A few areas of Dallas also extend into other school districts in Dallas County, including Carrollton-Farmers Branch, Coppell, Duncanville, Garland, Highland Park, Irving, Mesquite, and Richardson.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Portions of Dallas in Collin County are in Plano ISD, and portions of Dallas in Denton County are in the Carrollton-Farmers Branch ISD.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The Wilmer-Hutchins Independent School District once served portions of southern Dallas, but it was shut down for the 2005–2006 year.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] WHISD students started attending other Dallas ISD schools during that time.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Following the close, the Texas Education Agency consolidated WHISD into Dallas ISD.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] In 2003 Royce Hanson, author of *Civic Culture and Urban Change: Governing Dallas*, stated that the Plano, Richardson, and Wilmer-Hutchins school districts were the "most significant" of the public school students with students in Dallas who were not in Dallas ISD.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Many school districts in Dallas County, including Dallas ISD, were formerly served by a governmental agency called Dallas County Schools.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] The system provided busing and other transportation services, access to a massive media library, technology services, strong ties to local organizations for education/community integration, and staff development programs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p02] Students from Dallas attend many private schools in Dallas, and in nearby areas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas has several local newspapers, magazines, television stations and radio stations that serve the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex, which is the fifth-largest media market in the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas has one major daily newspaper, *The Dallas Morning News*, which was founded in 1885 by A.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The *Dallas Times Herald*, started in 1888, was the *Morning News'* major competitor until Belo purchased it on December 8, 1991, and closed the paper down the next day.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Other daily newspapers are *Al Día*, a Spanish-language paper published by Belo, and a number of ethnic newspapers printed in languages such as Chinese, Korean, and Vietnamese.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Other publications include the *Dallas Weekly* and the *Elite News*, all weekly news publications.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The *Dallas Observer* and the *North Texas Journal* are also alternative weekly newspapers.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] *The Dallas Morning News* formerly had a weekly publication, *Neighborsgo*, which came out every Friday and focused on community news.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Readers could post stories and contribute content to the website.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In terms of the larger metro area, the *Fort Worth Star-Telegram* is another major daily newspaper, covering Fort Worth's metropolitan division.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] It also publishes a major Spanish-language newspaper for the entire metro area known as *La Estrella*.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] To the north of Dallas and Fort Worth, the *Denton Record-Chronicle* primarily covers news for the city of Denton and Denton County.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] KTXA 21 and KFAA 29 are an independent stations; KTXA was previously affiliated with the now-defunct UPN network.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Over 101 radio stations operate within range of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas operates WRR 101.1 FM, the area's main classical music station, from city offices in Fair Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Its original sister station, licensed as WRR in 1921, is the oldest commercially operated radio station in Texas and claims to be the second-oldest in the United States, after KDKA in Pittsburgh.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] KKDA-FM (K104), an urban contemporary station, and KRNB (Smooth R&B 105.7), an urban adult contemporary station, are owned independently by Service Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Slavic Voice of America media group serves Russian-speaking Americans out of Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Hispanic Broadcasting Corporation (HBC), the largest company in the Spanish-language radio station business, is based in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In 2003, HBC was acquired by Univision and became Univision Radio Inc., but the radio company remains headquartered in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Dallas Police Department provides most policing in Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Dallas Chief of Police is Daniel Comeaux.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The police headquarters are in the Cedars neighborhood of southern Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Emergency medical services and fire protection in the city are provided by the Dallas Fire-Rescue Department.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Dallas Fire & Rescue chief is Dominique Artis.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The department operates the Dallas Firefighter's Museum built in 1907 along Parry Avenue near Fair Park.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas's oldest remaining fire station building still stands at the corner of McKinney Ave. and Leonard and was built in 1892.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Number 1, and is now a picture framing shop.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas has many hospitals and several medical research facilities within its city limits.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] One major research center is the Dallas Medical District with the UT Southwestern Medical Center in the Stemmons Corridor, along with the affiliated UT Southwestern Medical School.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The health care complex includes within its bounds Parkland Memorial Hospital, Children's Medical Center, William P.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Paul University Hospital), and the William P.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas also has a VA hospital in the southern portion of the city, the Dallas Veterans Affairs Medical Center.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The center is home to a Consolidated Mail Outpatient Pharmacy (CMOP), part of an initiative by the Department of Veterans Affairs to provide mail-order prescriptions to veterans using computerization at strategic locations throughout the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas is served by Dallas Water Utilities, which operates several waste treatment plants and pulls water from several area reservoirs.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Several companies maintain the city's electric system, including Stream Energy, Cirro Energy and Oncor Electric Delivery, whose parent company, Energy Future Holdings Corporation, has headquarters in the city.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The city offers garbage pickup and recycling service weekly through its Sanitation Services department.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Telephone networks, broadband internet, and cable television service are available from several companies, including AT&T, Spectrum, and Verizon FiOS.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In 2009, 78.5% of Dallas (city) commuters drive to work alone.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The 2009 mode share for Dallas (city) commuters are 10.7% for carpooling, 3.9% for transit, 1.9% for walking, and .1% for cycling.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In 2015, the American Community Survey estimated modal shares for Dallas (city) commuters of 75.4% for driving alone, 12.8% for carpooling, 3.5% for riding transit, 1.9% for walking, and .2% for cycling.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In 2015, 10.2 percent of Dallas households lacked a car, decreased to 9.1 percent in 2016 and to 8.7 percent in 2023.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas averaged 1.59 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas is at the confluence of four major interstate highways—Interstates 20, 30, 35E, and 45.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Dallas area freeway system is set up in the popular hub-and-spoke system, shaped much like a wagon wheel.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Starting from the center of the city, a small freeway loop surrounds Downtown, followed by the I-635 loop about 10 miles (16 km) outside Downtown, and ultimately the tolled President George Bush Turnpike.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Inside these freeway loops are other boulevard- and parkway-style loops, including Loop 12 and Belt Line Road.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Another beltway around the city upwards of 45 miles (72 km) from Downtown is under plan in Collin County.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Radiating out of Downtown Dallas's freeway loop are the spokes of the area's highway system—Interstates 30, 35E, and 45, US 75, US 77, US 175, SH Spur 366, the Dallas North Tollway, SH 114, US 80, and US 67.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Other major highways around the city include SH 183 and Spur 408.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The recently completed interchange at the intersection of Lyndon B.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Johnson Freeway (I-635) and the Central Expressway (US 75) has five stacks and is aptly called the High Five Interchange.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] It is one of the few five-level interchanges in Dallas and is one of the largest freeway interchanges in the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Two commercial airports serve Dallas: Dallas Fort Worth International Airport and Dallas Love Field.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In addition, Dallas Executive Airport (formerly Redbird Airport), serves as a general aviation airport for the city, and Addison Airport functions similarly just outside the city limits in the suburb of Addison.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Two more general aviation airports are about 35 miles (56 km) north of Dallas in McKinney, and another two are in Fort Worth, on the west side of the metroplex.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Alliance Airport, in far North Fort Worth, is a cargo reliever airport to DFW Airport and general aviation facility.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] DFW Airport is in the suburbs slightly north of and equidistant to Downtown Fort Worth and Downtown Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In terms of size, DFW International is the largest airport in the state, the second largest in the United States, and ninth largest in the world; DFW International Airport is larger than the island of Manhattan.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In terms of traffic, DFW Airport is the busiest airport in the state, fourth-busiest in the United States, and eleventh-busiest in the world.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The headquarters of American Airlines, the largest air carrier in the world ahead of United Airlines and Delta Air Lines, is less than one mile (1.6 km) from DFW Airport within Fort Worth's city limits.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Similarly, Love Field is within Dallas's city limits, about 6 miles (10 km) northwest of Downtown, and is headquarters to Southwest Airlines, the largest domestic airline in the United States.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas Area Rapid Transit (DART) is the Dallas-area public transportation authority that provides rail, buses and HOV lanes to commuters.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] DART began operating the first light rail system in Texas in 1996, and it is now the largest operator of light rail in the US.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Today, the system is the seventh-busiest light rail system in the country with approximately 55 stations on 72 miles (116 km) of light rail, and 10 stations on 35 miles (56 km) of commuter rail.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] It includes four light rail lines and a commuter line: the Red Line, the Blue Line, the Green Line, the Orange Line, and the Trinity Railway Express.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Red Line travels through Oak Cliff, South Dallas, Downtown, Uptown, North Dallas, Richardson and Plano, while the Blue Line goes through Oak Cliff, Downtown, Uptown, East Dallas, Lake Highlands, and Garland.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Red and Blue lines are conjoined between 8th & Corinth Station in Oak Cliff through Mockingbird Station in North Dallas.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The two lines service Cityplace Station.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Green Line serves Carrollton, Farmers Branch, Love Field Airport, Stemmons Corridor, Victory Park, Downtown, Deep Ellum, Fair Park, South Dallas, and Pleasant Grove.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Orange Line initially operated as a peak-service line providing extra capacity on portions of the Green and Red Lines (Bachman Station on the Green Line, through the Downtown transit mall, to Parker Road Station on the Red Line making a "U"-shape).
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] However, the first stage of the Orange Line opened on December 6, 2010, extending its west end from Bachman to Belt Line Station in Irving.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The second and final phase opened in August 2014 and provided DFW Airport with rail service.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] DFW Airport Terminal A station is the terminus for the Orange Line and connects Skylink.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] This provides passengers the convenience of disembarking the DART rail, proceeding to security check-in and immediately boarding Skylink to be quickly transported to their desired terminal.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Blue Line has also been extended by 4.5 miles (7.2 km) to serve Rowlett at the Rowlett Park & Ride facility.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In August 2009, the Regional Transportation Council agreed to seek $96 million in federal stimulus dollars for a trolley project in Dallas and Fort Worth.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Oak Cliff Transit Authority took the lead with leaders envisioning a streetcar line that would link Union Station and the Dallas Convention Center in Downtown to Oak Cliff, Methodist Medical Center, and the Bishop Arts District via the Houston Street Viaduct.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] Dallas was awarded a $23 million TIGER grant towards the $58 million Dallas Streetcar Project in February 2010.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] In addition to light rail, Amtrak's *Texas Eagle* also serves Union Station, providing daily service east to Chicago and west to San Antonio, and thrice-weekly service west to Los Angeles.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The Trinity Rail Express terminates at Union Station and T&P Station.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The city of Dallas has worked to build Sister & Friendship City relationships around the globe.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] These relationships help create and strengthen partnerships between Dallas and the international community.
[src:cleveland-ohio/dallas-p03] The program aims to build global cooperation at the municipal level by promoting cultural understanding and stimulating economic development between Dallas and its foreign counterparts.
